
const STATIONS=[
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a housemate. Stan, your university housemate, has recently decided to adopt a vegan diet. He has become passionate about being vegan, and loves talking about his reduced carbon footprint and contribution to animal welfare. At your latest dinner, Stan stated that he doesn't feel right about living in a house where animal products are regularly bought and used. He feels so strongly about this that he offers to do all the grocery shopping and cooking for everyone if you will all agree to no longer bring animal products into the house. Otherwise, he feels he will have to move out.",prompt1:"What would you say to Stan and your other housemates?",prompt2:"What is your approach to working with someone whose beliefs are vastly different from your own?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are an employee paired with Ryan at a financial consulting firm. Your boss asks you both to complete a major industry report by Monday morning. After she leaves, Ryan says: \"I'm totally wiped. I was going to get my guy to drop off some Adderall to get us through the weekend. It really helps me get things done faster. Do you want a couple?\"",prompt1:"How would you respond to Ryan's question?",prompt2:"Do you think universities should be more proactive in preventing widespread Adderall misuse among their students?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are in a study group. A friend obtained last year's exam from a teaching assistant and forwarded it to everyone. Immediately after, Marcine - another member - emails you privately to say she will report the breach to the professor with everyone's names, and asks you not to warn the others so they can't 'hide the evidence.'",prompt1:"Do you think Marcine's approach is fair? Why or why not?",prompt2:"What would you do?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"In your study group, John is upset that Marshal's workload was redistributed after Marshal was hospitalised. A photo has since appeared on Marshal's Facebook showing him at a pool party. The group's work, if submitted, would give Marshal the same grade despite not contributing. Steve turns to you and asks how to proceed.",prompt1:"What do you recommend to your group members?",prompt2:"Do you think it is okay to report a concern to a supervisor based on a suspicion? Why or why not?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are captain of your high school basketball team preparing for regional championships next week. Your mother calls in distress - her sister has died unexpectedly. Your aunt was not close to the family and you barely know her. The funeral is the same day as your championships, four hours away by car, and you don't have a driver's licence.",prompt1:"Do you attend the funeral or the game? Why?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to make a similarly challenging decision."},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a university student. You have been selected for a prestigious internship overseas that begins in three months. Your younger brother has just been diagnosed with a serious mental illness and is struggling. Your parents are managing but are clearly overwhelmed. The internship is a once-in-a-decade opportunity.",prompt1:"What factors are you weighing, and what do you decide?",prompt2:"How do you think about your obligations to your family versus your obligations to yourself?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You work part-time at a café. Your manager has been scheduling you for shifts that conflict with your university timetable despite you giving her your availability weeks ago. When you raise it, she says the roster 'can't be changed now' and implies you should sort out your own shift swaps. Two colleagues have already said they can't swap.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"When a workplace policy or decision directly conflicts with your personal obligations, how do you approach resolving it?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student working in a campus café. A regular customer - a postgraduate student named Niamh - comes in looking severely distressed. While making her order, she mentions that her supervisor has told her if she doesn't submit her thesis by Friday she will be expelled from the program. She says she hasn't slept in four days and has been relying on energy drinks. As she pays, you notice her hands are trembling badly and she mentions offhand that she's been having heart palpitations but 'can't afford to stop now.'",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Niamh says: 'Please don't make this a bigger deal than it is - I just need my coffee.' How do you respond to this?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a resident in a shared apartment block. Your downstairs neighbour - a single mother of two young children - has knocked on your door asking if you could please stop using your treadmill before 7am, as the noise wakes her babies. You have been using the treadmill at 6am because it is the only time you have before work. She looks exhausted and apologises for bothering you. You have a medical condition that makes evening exercise difficult.",prompt1:"How would you respond to her in this moment?",prompt2:"What is a fair way to resolve a conflict where both parties have genuine and reasonable needs?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a final-year student who has just received a job offer from a prestigious company - the role you have worked toward for three years. The same week, your closest friend is diagnosed with a serious illness that will require a year of treatment. He doesn't ask you to change your plans, but you can see he is frightened and that his support network is thin. The job starts in three weeks.",prompt1:"What is going through your mind?",prompt2:"Give an example of a time in your life when you faced a genuine conflict between your own goals and the needs of someone close to you. What did you choose, and do you stand by it now?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a team leader at a community youth centre. One of your volunteers - a 19-year-old named Bea - has been working with at-risk teenagers for six months. She is energetic and the kids clearly like her. However, in the last few weeks you have noticed she has been sharing personal details of her own difficult past with the teenagers during sessions - including details about past drug use - in an attempt to build rapport. Two other staff have raised concerns with you privately.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation with Bea?",prompt2:"What is the line between appropriate self-disclosure and oversharing in a professional helping role - and who is harmed when that line is crossed?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a close friend. Your friend Daniel has been battling severe depression for the past year and has been isolating himself from most people. He has recently confided in you - and only you - that he has been secretly researching assisted dying options, not because he has a terminal illness, but because he feels his quality of life is unbearable. He hasn't said he is going to act on anything, and he was very clear that he only told you because he trusted you completely and does not want you to involve anyone else. You are genuinely worried.",prompt1:"What is going through your mind, and what do you say to Daniel in this moment?",prompt2:"Daniel asks you directly: 'You're not going to tell anyone, are you?' How do you respond?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a third-year university student and the president of your faculty's student society. Two of your most capable committee members - Sophie and Marcus - have had a serious falling out after a disagreement at a social event last month. They are now refusing to work together, which is causing real problems as they co-lead your biggest event of the year. Other committee members are starting to take sides. The event is six weeks away and cannot be delayed.",prompt1:"How would you approach Sophie and Marcus individually, and what would you say?",prompt2:"Some committee members are suggesting you simply remove one of them from the event to resolve the tension quickly. What are your thoughts on this approach?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a university student in your final semester. Your father, who immigrated to this country and worked two jobs for twenty years specifically so you could get a degree, has been diagnosed with an aggressive form of cancer. He has been given 6-12 months. He tells you not to worry about him and insists you focus on finishing your degree. Your mother, however, calls you crying every second night, saying she cannot manage alone and needs you to come home. Your home is a 5-hour drive away.",prompt1:"What is going through your mind, and what do you do?",prompt2:"Your father finds out your mother has been calling you and apologises, saying: 'She shouldn't have done that - this is not your burden.' How does this change, if at all, how you think about the situation?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a retail employee. You are working alone on a quiet weekday. An elderly woman comes in and begins carefully selecting items. You notice she is placing several low-value items into her bag without scanning them. She pays for a few things at the register and leaves. You are fairly certain this was intentional, but not completely sure.",prompt1:"What do you do in this moment?",prompt2:"How would your approach change if this were a teenager in school uniform, or a young mother with a child?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a volunteer at a community legal centre. A man in his 50s comes in asking for help with a tenancy dispute. As you begin to take his details, it becomes clear he is highly distressed and keeps veering off the practical issue - talking about his ex-wife, his estrangement from his children, and feeling like 'everything is falling apart.' He hasn't asked for emotional support. He came for legal help. Your supervisor is waiting for you to complete his intake form.",prompt1:"How do you handle this conversation?",prompt2:"What does this moment ask of you beyond your formal role - and how do you offer that without overstepping or making assumptions about what he needs?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. During an exam, you notice the person sitting next to you - someone you don't know - clearly reading from a folded piece of paper hidden in their sleeve. The exam is worth 40% of the grade and is graded on a curve, meaning their score directly affects yours. You are three rows from the invigilator and the exam ends in fifteen minutes.",prompt1:"What do you do in this moment, and what are the considerations pulling you in different directions?",prompt2:"The exam ends before you can do anything. What, if anything, do you do now?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a friend. A close friend Lena, whom you've known for six years, confides that she has been accepting money from her grandmother under false pretences - telling her grandmother the money is for university fees when in fact she has been spending it on rent and personal expenses. Her grandmother is in her 80s, lives alone, and has a modest fixed income. Lena does not seem troubled by this. She tells you she's 'not hurting anyone.'",prompt1:"What do you say to Lena in this conversation?",prompt2:"How do you think Lena has arrived at the belief that this isn't hurting anyone - and what does that tell you about how people justify actions they know are wrong?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a convenience store employee working a late shift alone. A man in his 40s comes in looking distressed and asks you if you have a first aid kit. He says his young daughter cut her hand badly in the carpark. You can see blood on his shirt. Your manager has a strict policy: employees must not leave the register unattended, and all medical situations must be referred to emergency services only.",prompt1:"What do you do right now?",prompt2:"When following policy would lead to an outcome that feels clearly wrong, how do you decide when to act against it - and who carries the responsibility for that decision?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a senior student in a small honours cohort of eight. One student, Marcus, has been dominating every group discussion - not maliciously, but with an intensity that leaves others visibly reluctant to contribute. Two other students have separately told you they've stopped trying to share ideas because they feel 'talked over.' The supervisor has not noticed. There are no formal mechanisms for raising this, and Marcus is a close friend of yours.",prompt1:"How do you approach this situation?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to address a friend's behaviour that was affecting others, even though they had no idea. What did you say, and how did they respond?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a team member on a community charity project. Your group has been fundraising for six months toward a specific cause. Two weeks before the final event, the project leader - without consulting the group - announces she has redirected a portion of the funds toward a different charity that she personally prefers, citing 'strategic realignment.' The original donors have not been told. Half the group privately agrees with your discomfort; the other half supports the leader's decision and says 'the outcome is still good.'",prompt1:"How do you respond to the leader, and what do you think needs to happen now?",prompt2:"Is 'the outcome is still good' a sufficient justification for changing how donated funds are used without transparency - and where does that reasoning lead if applied broadly?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a postgraduate student sharing an office with four others. One office-mate, Jin, has been playing lo-fi music quietly through a speaker for weeks. Most people haven't minded, but one student - Amara - has asked him twice to stop, saying it breaks her concentration. Jin has been politely apologetic each time but continues within a day or two. Amara has now come to you, clearly frustrated, and asks you to back her up when she raises it again as a group.",prompt1:"What do you say to Amara, and how do you approach the situation when the group is next together?",prompt2:"What is the difference between supporting a colleague and taking sides - and how do you navigate that distinction when both people have reasonable positions?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a volunteer coordinator for a charity that provides meals to homeless individuals. One of your most dedicated volunteers, a retired man named George who has been coming every Saturday for three years, has recently been making comments that some of the recipients find patronising and occasionally offensive. Two recipients have separately mentioned it to you. George is unaware and clearly means no harm.",prompt1:"How do you approach this with George?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to give critical feedback to someone who was well-intentioned but causing harm without realising it. What made that conversation difficult, and how did you handle it?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. Your housemate asks you to be the designated driver for a group night out. Late in the evening, you discover your housemate - who organised the whole night - has been secretly drinking despite telling everyone he was also staying sober so 'the numbers worked.' He is now asking you to drive a group of seven people home in a car that seats five, saying: 'No one will notice and it's just around the corner.'",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"How does the fact that your housemate deceived you about staying sober affect how you approach this situation?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a student representative on your university's academic integrity committee. A case is brought before the committee involving a student caught submitting an AI-generated essay. The student is a single parent who explains that she had a family emergency the week the essay was due, didn't ask for an extension because she 'didn't want to seem like she was making excuses,' and used AI in desperation. This is her first academic integrity violation.",prompt1:"How should the committee approach this case?",prompt2:"Do you think universities have kept pace with the ethical questions raised by AI-generated work? What policies would you recommend?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a shift supervisor at a retail store. Two of your employees - both of whom you consider good workers - have had a falling out over a scheduling dispute. One of them, Maya, has started leaving tasks incomplete that she knows the other, Sean, will have to finish. Sean has come to you saying he feels targeted and the situation is affecting his mental health. Maya denies it is intentional.",prompt1:"How do you handle this situation?",prompt2:"What does fairness look like when one party denies behaviour that the other person experiences as clearly intentional?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a second-year university student. A professor whose class you are enrolled in has given you a grade that you believe is unfair and that could significantly affect your academic record.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to advocate for yourself in a situation where you had significantly less power than the other person. What did you do, and how did it turn out?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"An elderly man - a 78-year-old Korean-Australian - has been referred to you after his neighbour reported concerns about his wellbeing. He arrived on time but is now sitting quietly, answering every question with 'I am fine' and offering polite, brief replies. His body language tells a different story. You have 30 minutes with him.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation?",prompt2:"What do you think is happening for this man beneath the surface - and what would genuine connection look like in this context?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a first-year intern at a company. Your team lead asks you to run a short training session for five colleagues on a new internal software platform. Halfway through, it becomes obvious the group is far more advanced than you assumed - two of them have already used the platform and are visibly frustrated. One makes a comment under their breath about it being a 'waste of time.'",prompt1:"What do you do right now, in this moment?",prompt2:"What does this experience teach you about the assumptions we make when preparing to communicate with an audience - and how do you recover gracefully when those assumptions are wrong?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a long-time employee at a small family-run business. The owner - a woman in her 60s who built the company from nothing and whom you genuinely respect - has been making decisions lately that seem increasingly erratic. She has double-booked major clients, forgotten conversations that happened recently, and become uncharacteristically emotional. You suspect she may be experiencing early cognitive decline. She has no family involved in the business, and you are her most trusted employee.",prompt1:"What is your responsibility here, if any, and what do you do?",prompt2:"How do you think your employer would feel if she knew you were having these concerns about her - and how does that shape your approach?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a volunteer visitor at a residential aged care facility. You regularly visit an 84-year-old resident named Arthur, who has no family and few visitors. During today's visit, Arthur becomes emotional and tells you that he overheard two staff members last week laughing about how he 'probably won't last the winter.' He is not visibly unwell. He says he hasn't slept since hearing it and asks you: 'Do you think they're right?'",prompt1:"What do you say to Arthur in this moment?",prompt2:"How do you think Arthur has been experiencing the time since he overheard those comments, and what does that tell you about the impact of careless words in care settings?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a second-year student on a group project. Your group's final presentation is tomorrow. Tonight, reviewing the shared document, you discover that your group's highest-achieving member - who everyone relies on and who volunteered to compile the final version - has inserted three paragraphs that were clearly taken directly from an online source, unreferenced and unacknowledged. The rest of your contributions are entirely original. If submitted as-is, the entire group will have a plagiarism violation on their record.",prompt1:"What do you do tonight?",prompt2:"If your group member insists the paragraphs were 'just a placeholder that they forgot to rewrite,' how do you assess that explanation, and does it change anything?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a postgraduate student. A close friend and fellow student, someone you have known for five years, is applying for the same highly competitive scholarship as you. You both need this scholarship - it would fund two years of your research. The committee has informally told you that you are the front-runner. Your friend asks if you would be willing to review his application and give honest feedback, the way you always have for each other. His application, as it stands, is weak in two specific ways that you can clearly see.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Describe a time when your loyalty to a friend and your own self-interest genuinely pulled against each other. How did you decide what to do, and how did it turn out?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a second-year university student. A member of your group project team - someone you don't know well - has listed significantly more contributions than they actually made on the group's self-assessment form. Their listed contributions overlap with yours in a way that, if accepted, would suggest your individual contribution was smaller than it was. The form is due tonight. You became aware of this by accident.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"What are the downstream harms when people misrepresent collaborative work - and what makes it particularly hard to address?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are an intern at a reputable firm. Your supervisor is brilliant and has been a strong advocate for you - but in group settings, you've noticed she consistently interrupts and speaks over the more junior women in the team in a way she doesn't do with the men. The pattern is subtle enough that you think she might not be aware of it. You are the most junior person in the room when it happens. No one else has said anything.",prompt1:"Do you say something - and if so, to whom and how?",prompt2:"Give an example of a time you noticed a pattern of behaviour - not a single incident - that you felt was wrong, but where speaking up felt risky or uncomfortable. What did you do, and what factors shaped that decision?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You have just started a graduate position and are keen to make a good impression. A senior colleague you respect asks you to cover for them with a client - to say they are 'in a meeting' when in fact they've left early for a personal appointment. It's a small thing, they say, and the client won't notice. You can tell the request makes sense to them and they're not asking you to do anything they'd consider significant.",prompt1:"How do you respond to this colleague in the moment?",prompt2:"Give an example of a time early in a job, volunteer role, or team setting where you were asked - directly or indirectly - to compromise on something you valued. How did you respond, and what did that experience shape in you?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"Your younger sister tells you she's dropping out of her law degree in her final semester. She says she's already decided and just wanted to tell you - not to be talked out of it. But you can hear that she's scared, and some of her reasons don't fully add up. Your parents don't know yet and she's asked you not to tell them.",prompt1:"What do you say to her right now - in this conversation?",prompt2:"She's asking you to keep a secret that you believe might harm her and will almost certainly affect your whole family. At what point does keeping someone's confidence become its own kind of harm?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You volunteer at a community centre running a weekly drop-in for older residents. One regular, Margaret, has recently made comments suggesting she is deeply isolated - she's mentioned some weeks this is 'the only real conversation I have.' She is proud and would be embarrassed to be treated as a welfare concern. Today she said offhandedly: 'I sometimes wonder if I'd even be missed.'",prompt1:"How do you respond to Margaret in this moment?",prompt2:"Her comment could mean very little or quite a lot - you genuinely can't tell. What does real care look like when you don't want to overstep but can't afford to underreact?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a junior employee at a non-profit that raises money for children's cancer research. While preparing quarterly reports, you discover that approximately 15% of all donations - clearly labelled by donors as being for research - have routinely been redirected to administrative costs and a staff retreat. Your manager, who approved the redirections, is widely respected in the sector and has dedicated 20 years to this organisation. The donors are not aware. You are two weeks into the job and on a probationary contract.",prompt1:"What do you do, and what are the second-order consequences of each path you are considering - including doing nothing?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you received feedback that you behaved wrongly in a situation where you genuinely believed you had done the right thing. How did you process it, and what changed, if anything, in how you acted afterward?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a final-year student completing a group research project worth 50% of your grade. There are four of you. One group member, Priya, has fallen significantly behind due to what she says is a family health crisis - though she has been vague about the details. The group has quietly absorbed her workload for six weeks. With submission due in nine days, the two other members are now telling you privately that they plan to contact the supervisor and have Priya's name removed from the project entirely. They want you to co-sign the request. Priya has contributed some work - just not proportional to the others. You are the informal group leader.",prompt1:"How do you approach this - both with Priya and with your other group members - and what outcome are you actually trying to achieve?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you found collaboration genuinely difficult - not because of conflict, but because someone's circumstances made equal contribution impossible. How did you navigate the tension between fairness and compassion?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a final-year student completing a placement at a law firm. A senior partner asks you to draft a letter to a client advising them that their case is strong - but after reviewing the file yourself, you believe the case is significantly weaker than the partner has represented. The client, who is elderly and has limited resources, has already told the partner she intends to sell her home to fund the litigation. The partner is under pressure to retain high-value clients and has been at the firm for 25 years. You are not qualified to give legal advice.",prompt1:"What do you do, and how do you weigh the competing obligations in this situation - to the partner, to the client, and to your own integrity?",prompt2:"Tell me about a time when you had to say no to someone in a position of authority over you. What made it hard, and how did you do it?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a university tutor. One of your students, James, has been attending every class and clearly working hard, but his written work is consistently poor - his arguments are muddled, his structure is weak, and he is at risk of failing the unit. You have provided written feedback twice. In today's consultation, he arrives with a printed copy of your feedback, tells you he has followed every suggestion, and asks you directly: 'Am I going to pass?' He seems anxious and is clearly hoping for reassurance. Looking at his revised draft, which he has brought with him, the improvements are minimal - he has made surface changes but the core problems remain.",prompt1:"What do you say to James - right now, in this conversation? Be specific about how you balance honesty with care, given the gap between his effort and his progress.",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to give someone genuinely difficult feedback that you knew would be hard for them to hear. What did you say, how did they respond, and looking back, do you think you handled it well?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. A close friend, Alex, confides that he has been using AI tools to generate substantial portions of his assessed essays all year. He says 'everyone is doing it' and that the rules are 'outdated and unenforceable.' He also tells you that he came in second for a scholarship last semester - a scholarship that you know another student, who does not use AI, narrowly won. He's not asking for your opinion; he's sharing this as if it's unremarkable. You care about Alex and also believe strongly in the integrity of academic assessment.",prompt1:"What do you say to Alex in this moment, if anything - and how do you think about the boundary between a friend's confidences and your own values?",prompt2:"Describe a time when a friend asked you to be complicit in something - or simply stay silent about something - that you thought was wrong. What did you do, and what did it cost you?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are one of twelve strangers selected for a social experiment. Each participant is given $500 cash and a simple choice: keep it entirely, split it 50/50 with the stranger sitting across from you, or donate your full $500 anonymously to a charity of your choice. You cannot communicate with the other person before deciding. You will never meet them again. No one will ever know what you chose.",prompt1:"What do you choose - and be honest about the full reasoning, including the parts that don't reflect well on you.",prompt2:"The fact that no one would ever know what you chose is the most important part of this scenario. What does your answer - when there are no social consequences at all - tell you about who you actually are?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a graduate student. Your research supervisor, Dr. Nguyen, is brilliant and has opened many doors for you - but over the past year, you have noticed a pattern: she regularly presents your ideas in seminars without crediting you, and in a recent grant application, a framework you developed appears under her name alone. When you raised it once, gently, she said you were 'misremembering' and changed the subject. Other students in her lab seem aware but say nothing. You are twelve months from submitting your thesis and depend heavily on her reference.",prompt1:"What are your options here - and what do you actually do, weighing the real stakes of your situation against your sense of what is right?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you experienced a situation that felt unfair, but where speaking up carried a real personal cost. What did you decide, and how do you feel about that decision now?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a recently appointed team leader in a healthcare administrative role. Your team has six members. One of them, Robert, is a 58-year-old long-term employee who has been in the organisation for 22 years - far longer than you have been alive. He consistently resists process changes, frequently says 'we tried that before,' and in team meetings talks over younger members. He is not unpleasant; he is simply very set in his ways and has significant informal authority among the older staff. You need his buy-in for a new workflow that will affect every member of the team.",prompt1:"How do you approach Robert - and how do you think about the difference between resistance that comes from genuine experience and resistance that comes from comfort with the status quo?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to work closely with someone whose style or values were very different from yours, and the collaboration was genuinely difficult. What did you learn about yourself from that experience?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a student. Your university has a clear policy that all academic work must be your own unless collaboration is explicitly permitted. A classmate - someone you're not close to but who you know is going through a difficult time after a bereavement - approaches you the night before a major assignment is due. She asks if she can 'look at' your completed draft 'just to get an idea of the structure.' You know from past experience that when students in your course have shared drafts this way, the resulting submissions have sometimes been too similar. You also know the assignment is submitted through plagiarism detection software.",prompt1:"What do you say - and how do you hold compassion for her situation alongside your responsibility to the integrity of your own work and to fair assessment?",prompt2:"Tell me about a time when someone you knew was struggling asked you for something you felt you couldn't give them. How did you say no, and how did it affect you and the relationship?"},
{category:"Policy",scenario:"There is increasing debate in Australia about mandatory reporting obligations for teachers - specifically, whether teachers who develop a genuine concern about a student's welfare at home should be legally required to report to child protection authorities, even in ambiguous cases where the evidence is limited and a report could fracture a family unnecessarily. Opponents argue that mandatory reporting in uncertain cases leads to over-reporting, traumatises families unfairly, and erodes trust between schools and vulnerable families. Proponents argue that children's safety must override all other considerations and that the system relies on professionals having the courage to report.",prompt1:"What are the strongest arguments on each side - and what framework would you use to guide a teacher who genuinely doesn't know whether to report a specific case?",prompt2:"Has there been a time in your own life when you saw something that concerned you about how a child was being treated, and you had to decide whether it was your place to act or speak up? What did you do, and what drove that decision?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a first-year employee at a consulting firm. A colleague, Tom, has been sending weekly team emails summarising 'key insights' - and several people have quietly mentioned to you that Tom's summaries consistently include ideas that originated in conversations you and others had, presented as if they are Tom's own synthesis. Tom is well-liked and ambitious. Your manager has started praising Tom in meetings for his 'strategic thinking.' No one else has raised it. You are not sure if Tom is doing this consciously or if he simply doesn't realise he is recycling others' ideas without attribution.",prompt1:"What do you do - and how does your uncertainty about Tom's intent shape how you approach it?",prompt2:"Have you ever had your work or your ideas claimed by someone else - or felt that your contribution was made invisible? How did it make you feel, and how, if at all, did you respond?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a pharmacy student on placement. A regular customer - an older man you have seen many times - comes in to collect his prescription. While processing it, you notice that the dose on his current prescription has been increased significantly compared to his previous one. When you mention this, he becomes flustered and says the doctor 'forgot to note something' and asks you to fill it anyway. You cannot reach the prescribing GP. Your supervising pharmacist is busy with another customer and has previously told you that 'old Bill' is reliable and 'not to make a fuss.'",prompt1:"What do you do - and how do you manage the competing pressures from your supervisor, the patient's request, and your own professional responsibilities?",prompt2:"Tell me about a time when you were put under pressure by someone you respected or depended on to do something that you felt was wrong. How did you respond, and what did that experience reveal about how you handle authority?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a third-year university student. Your study group of five people has been together for two years and you are close. One member, Diane, was recently diagnosed with anxiety and has shared this openly with the group. Since then, another member - Ben - has started making all group decisions around Diane's comfort: changing meeting times, avoiding topics, and softening feedback on her work. Two other members have told you privately that they feel the group has stopped functioning as an honest intellectual environment, and that protecting Diane has become a form of overcorrection. Diane herself has not asked for this and seems unaware it is happening.",prompt1:"What is the actual problem here - and how do you approach it in a way that is fair to Diane, honest with Ben, and preserves the integrity of the group?",prompt2:"Describe a time when good intentions - yours or someone else's - created a dynamic that was harmful in a way no one intended. What did you do, and what did it teach you about the limits of trying to protect people?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a volunteer at a youth mentorship program. One of the young people you mentor, a 15-year-old named Jayden, tells you that he has been regularly selling small amounts of cannabis to friends at school to earn money because his family's financial situation is dire - his mother has recently lost her job. He tells you he trusts you and has never told any adult before. He is not a user himself; he says he is doing it 'to help out.' He asks you to keep it confidential. The program has a clear confidentiality policy, but it also has a mandatory disclosure clause for situations involving 'ongoing risk of harm to the young person.'",prompt1:"What do you do - and how do you think about the relationship between Jayden's trust in you, your duty of care, and the real consequences for him if you disclose versus if you don't?",prompt2:"Tell me about a time when keeping someone's confidence came into conflict with what you believed was the right thing to do. What did you decide, and how did it affect your relationship with that person?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are at a crowded train station. You notice a man in his 60s drop his wallet and keep walking - he hasn't noticed. Before you can act, a teenager picks it up, looks around, sees you watching, makes eye contact, and then deliberately pockets it and walks in the opposite direction. The original owner is still visible about 30 metres ahead.",prompt1:"What do you do right now - and walk through every competing thought that runs through your head in that moment.",prompt2:"The teenager looked directly at you before pocketing the wallet. What do you think that moment of eye contact meant - and does being a witness to something change your responsibility to act?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a student who has just started a research placement under a well-known academic, Professor Walsh. On your third day, you discover that a dataset underlying one of Professor Walsh's recently published papers appears to contain values that don't match the raw data files you have been asked to organise - the published figures appear cleaner than the raw data would support. You are not an expert in the statistical methods used. You could be wrong. But you could also be right. Professor Walsh is highly regarded, and this placement is connected to a scholarship you are hoping to receive.",prompt1:"What do you do - step by step - and how do you manage the profound uncertainty you have about whether you are seeing what you think you are seeing?",prompt2:"Tell me about a time when you noticed something that seemed wrong in a context where raising it carried a real personal risk. What did you do - and honestly, were you proud of how you handled it?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"At a family dinner, your uncle makes a casually derogatory comment about a minority group - not a slur, but the kind of remark the table absorbs without reaction. Your elderly grandmother is sitting right there and is easily distressed. Your parents catch your eye and give you a look that clearly means: leave it.",prompt1:"Do you say something? Walk through your actual reasoning in the moment - not the ideal version.",prompt2:"There is a version of 'picking your battles' that is genuine wisdom and a version that is just avoidance with a respectable name. How do you tell the difference - and which one is this?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You have been offered a place in a prestigious university exchange program you have worked toward for two years. It starts in six weeks. Last week, your father was diagnosed with a serious illness. He is not in immediate danger, but the next six months will involve frequent appointments, and your mother is already stretched. Your father has told you clearly and repeatedly: 'Go. I don't want this to stop you.'",prompt1:"What do you do - and how do you actually make that decision?",prompt2:"Your father is telling you what he thinks you need to hear. How do you navigate a situation where the person you're trying to care for is actively making it harder for you to do so?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You have been close friends with someone for eight years. Lately the friendship has become one-sided - you initiate almost all contact, they cancel regularly, and when you do catch up, the conversation is almost entirely about them. Last week you brought up something difficult you were going through and they changed the subject within a minute.",prompt1:"What do you do - do you say something, and if so, how?",prompt2:"There's a difference between a friendship going through a hard patch and one that has genuinely changed. How do you tell the difference - and what does loyalty ask of you in each case?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You tutor a first-year university subject. One student, James, is bright but regularly talks over quieter students, dominates discussion, and has made a couple of comments that landed badly in the group. You don't think he's malicious - he seems genuinely unaware. After last week's session, two other students separately told you they no longer feel comfortable speaking up when James is in the room.",prompt1:"How do you address this with James, and when?",prompt2:"James almost certainly doesn't see himself the way those two students do. What does it mean to give feedback to someone who has no idea they're causing harm - and what is your responsibility if they don't respond to it?"},
{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a student representative on your university's faculty board. During a meeting, a senior professor dismisses a proposal you raised - one drawn directly from a student survey - with the comment: 'Students mean well but they don't understand how institutions actually work.' No one at the table responds. You have to continue working with this professor for the rest of the year.",prompt1:"How do you respond in the room - and what, if anything, do you do afterwards?",prompt2:"Being dismissed by someone with more institutional power is a particular kind of frustration. How do you stay effective inside a system where the people you need to influence don't take you seriously?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a student. You have been short-listed for a prestigious scholarship. The final stage involves a panel interview. The night before your interview, a friend who interviewed earlier in the day messages you to tell you the exact questions that were asked in his panel - he sends them unprompted, saying he wants to help you. You did not ask for this. You do not know whether the same questions will be asked again. The scholarship is transformative - it would fund the rest of your degree.",prompt1:"What do you do with this information - and how do you reason about whether receiving it, even unsolicited, creates an unfair advantage or an ethical problem?",prompt2:"Tell me about a situation where you were given an advantage - in an academic or competitive context - that you weren't sure you had earned or that others didn't have. How did you feel about it, and did it change how you acted?"},
{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a newly qualified social worker. Your client is a 34-year-old woman, Natasha, who has two young children and is attempting to leave a long-term abusive relationship. She has a safety plan in place. Today she tells you - calmly and clearly - that she has decided to go back to her partner. She gives you reasons that are practical and considered: housing, money, the children's schooling. She is not in immediate danger. She has the legal right to make this choice. You are deeply concerned.",prompt1:"What do you say - in this conversation, right now - and how do you balance her right to self-determination against your knowledge of what research tells us about the danger of this decision?",prompt2:"Have you ever watched someone you care about make a decision you were certain would harm them, and had to decide how hard to push back? What did you say, how far did you go, and how do you feel about that now?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a junior employee. Your company has recently adopted an AI tool to assist with hiring decisions - it screens CVs and ranks candidates before human reviewers see them. You have been asked to help review the system's outputs to check for quality. Going through the data, you notice a clear pattern: candidates with names commonly associated with certain ethnic backgrounds are being ranked significantly lower, even when their qualifications are comparable or superior to higher-ranked candidates. Your manager, who implemented the system, is proud of the efficiency gains and has staked some professional credibility on it.",prompt1:"What do you do - and how do you think about your responsibility when you identify a systemic problem that implicates the decisions of someone above you?",prompt2:"Tell me about a time when you identified something unfair happening in an institution or system you were part of - a school, employer, sports team, or organisation. Did you speak up? Why or why not, and what do you think the right answer was?"},
{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a second-year student. Your closest friend in your course, Jamie, has been struggling significantly - failing assessments, withdrawing socially, and clearly not okay. You have been Jamie's primary support for the past three months: answering calls at 2am, sitting with them through panic attacks, helping them draft emails to professors. You genuinely care about Jamie. But you have noticed that your own performance is slipping, you've missed deadlines, and you feel emotionally exhausted. Jamie has not engaged with any of the professional resources you've suggested, and seems to rely more heavily on you the more support you give.",prompt1:"What is your responsibility here - to Jamie, and to yourself - and what do you actually do?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to set a limit on how much of yourself you could give to someone who needed help. What made it hard to do, and how did you find the words?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are the coordinator of a voluntary community group that organises mental health support events for university students. The group has eight regular volunteers. A long-standing volunteer, David, is well-liked and has contributed enormously over three years. Recently, however, other volunteers have raised concerns with you: David has been sharing identifiable details about students who have attended your events - not maliciously, just casually, over drinks - in a way that clearly breaches the group's confidentiality norms. The students affected don't know. David would be shocked and mortified if he understood the impact. You have no formal authority over David.",prompt1:"How do you approach this with David - and what do you do about the students whose information has already been shared, given they are unaware?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to address a friend or colleague's behaviour that was causing harm to others, and they had no idea. What did you say, what was their reaction, and how do you evaluate how you handled it?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a member of a student research group. Over several months, you notice that one member consistently takes more credit than is due in group presentations, while another quieter member whose contributions are substantial is consistently uncredited. Neither has raised it.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Why do you think the uncredited member hasn't raised it themselves - and what does that tell you about the dynamics at play?",prompt3:"You've decided to address this, but the credit-taking member responds by saying 'I do most of the work anyway, and [quiet member] never speaks up, so they obviously don't mind.' How do you handle this pushback?",prompt4:"Imagine you're now the research supervisor who becomes aware of this pattern across multiple student groups. What systemic changes would you implement to prevent this dynamic from occurring?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are part-time shift supervisor at a café. Two of your team members, Bec and Yusuf, have a running personality clash that has started affecting everyone's experience at work. You've tried talking to them separately. Each one privately insists the other is the problem. Yesterday they had a visible argument in front of customers. Your manager saw it and has told you to resolve it by Friday - or she will.",prompt1:"What do you actually do before Friday?",prompt2:"Your manager's ultimatum forces you toward a fast resolution. What are the risks of pressuring two people to reconcile on a deadline - and when is a visible fix actually worse than no fix at all?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a friend. Your close friend, Mira, has been in a relationship for three years with someone you have never trusted. Last week, while housesitting for Mira, you accidentally saw messages on her partner's phone - left open on a bench - that make it clear he is being romantically dishonest with her. You were not snooping. Mira is deeply committed to this relationship and has told you previously that she and her ex-best friend fell out because 'that friend never trusted my choices.' She is happy. You do not know how Mira would receive this information.",prompt1:"What do you do - and what are the competing values at stake when someone's right to know something conflicts with the circumstances under which you came to know it?",prompt2:"Tell me about a time when you had to decide whether to tell a friend something that you knew might damage your friendship. What did you decide, and how has it affected the relationship since?"},
{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a university student working on a group assignment worth 40% of your grade. One member, Darren, has done almost nothing - missed meetings, submitted drafts full of errors, and gone quiet for weeks. The rest of the group has silently absorbed his share. With one week to go, Darren reappears and asks to be listed as an equal contributor, saying he had a family emergency he didn't want to share. No one in the group had any idea.",prompt1:"How do you respond to Darren, and what do you think is the fair outcome here?",prompt2:"Darren's situation made him invisible to the group until he needed something from them. What does that tell you about how teams handle people who are struggling in silence?"},
{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. Your close friend asks you to proofread their scholarship application essay. While reading it, you recognise two paragraphs lifted almost word-for-word from an article - without citation. When you mention it, your friend says: 'It's just a scholarship, not coursework. No one checks these. And I genuinely need the money.' Their financial situation is real and difficult.",prompt1:"What do you do?",prompt2:"Your friend's argument is that the harm is essentially invisible - no one is hurt, no one will know. How do you think about ethical obligations in situations where the consequences of doing the wrong thing are genuinely hard to see?"},


{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a manager at a small café. One of your employees, Sofia, has been coming in five minutes late almost every shift for the past three weeks. She's one of your best workers - customers love her, she's never caused problems before, and the lateness hasn't yet caused real disruption. A newer employee, who is always punctual, has started making comments about it to colleagues. You haven't said anything to Sofia yet.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation with Sofia, and what do you say to the newer employee?",prompt2:"Describe a time in your own life when someone let a problem with you go unaddressed for too long before raising it. What was the effect of the delay - on you, on them, and on the situation?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are in your late twenties. Your parents have started strongly pressuring you to move back to the family home and eventually take over your father's small business. Your father has built it over 30 years and sees passing it to you as his retirement plan. You have a completely different career you are passionate about and have worked hard to build. You love your parents and understand what this means to them. You have not yet had a direct conversation with your father about your actual plans.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation with your father, and what do you say?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to disappoint someone who had invested a great deal of hope in you. How did you handle it, and how do you reflect on it now?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a first-year employee at a marketing agency. Your team is preparing a campaign for a client who sells nutritional supplements. Your manager asks you to write copy that describes a product as 'clinically proven to support weight loss.' Looking at the product's documentation, you can find no clinical trials - only a few small studies with inconclusive results. Your manager waves this off: 'Everyone writes it this way. It just means the ingredients have been studied somewhere.'",prompt1:"What do you say to your manager, and what do you actually do with the copy?",prompt2:"Describe a time when something that was described as 'normal' or 'everyone does it' turned out to feel wrong to you. How did you handle that tension between fitting in and maintaining your own standards?"},

{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a sibling. Your older brother, who is 34, has become increasingly isolated over the past year - he's quit his job, stopped seeing friends, and spends most of his time at home. When you visit, he seems fine on the surface but deflects every question about how he's really going. He's told you not to worry. Your parents are aware but are avoiding the topic because they don't want to push him away. You are the family member he is closest to.",prompt1:"What do you say to your brother - and how do you start a conversation he has already signalled he doesn't want to have?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to find a way into a difficult conversation with someone who was protecting themselves by keeping you out. What did you say, and what happened?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a final-year university student. You have just discovered that a close friend and housemate has been secretly telling others in your social group that you got your scholarship because of a connection - implying you didn't earn it on merit. You found out indirectly, through someone else. Your friend doesn't know you know. The claim is not true. You are hurt, confused, and angry.",prompt1:"What do you do - do you confront your friend, and if so, how?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you discovered that someone you trusted had said something about you that felt like a betrayal. How did you respond, and what did it reveal about your approach to conflict with people you care about?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a community sports coach for a team of 14-year-olds. One of your players, Kai, is clearly your most talented athlete - genuinely exceptional. His parents have started pushing you to give Kai special treatment: extra court time, exemption from team rules, and to exclude a less-skilled player from the squad so Kai 'doesn't waste time on weak teammates.' The parents have implied they'll pull Kai from the team if you don't comply. The team dynamic is good and the other kids like each other.",prompt1:"How do you respond to Kai's parents, and how do you handle the situation with the team?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you were pressured by someone with leverage to treat people differently or unfairly. How did you handle it, and what did that experience teach you about fairness under pressure?"},

{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a community leader organising a neighbourhood clean-up event. A resident, Paul, has been attending every meeting but consistently shoots down others' ideas, questions every decision, and this week posted a lengthy negative critique of your planning on the neighbourhood Facebook group - including some things that were factually wrong. Despite this, Paul also does more physical work than almost anyone else on the day. Other volunteers are becoming demoralised.",prompt1:"How do you approach Paul, and how do you manage the effect he's having on the group?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to work alongside someone who was both genuinely valuable and genuinely disruptive. How did you navigate holding both of those things at once?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You have just found out you didn't get a highly competitive position you had been working toward for two years. The rejection came with almost no feedback. A friend who is less experienced than you got the role. You feel devastated, confused, and a little envious - an emotion you're not used to feeling and don't like in yourself.",prompt1:"How do you process this - with yourself, and in how you show up for your friend?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you felt envious of someone - genuinely, not just briefly. How did you handle that feeling, and what does it tell you about what matters most to you?"},

{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a team leader at a tech startup. A new team member, Yasmin, is technically excellent but has a habit of sending long, detailed emails that bury the key message - her colleagues have started skimming or ignoring them entirely. Important information has been missed twice. Yasmin is proud of her thoroughness and clearly puts a lot of work into her communication. She hasn't received feedback on this before.",prompt1:"How do you raise this with Yasmin in a way that is honest, specific, and doesn't feel like a criticism of her effort?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you received feedback that changed something fundamental about the way you communicate. How did you respond in the moment, and how long did it take to actually integrate the feedback?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. You are part of a group chat with your cohort. One night, a classmate posts a photo taken without consent of another student in a compromising but not explicit situation - the kind of post intended to be funny. Most of the group laughs along. The student in the photo is not in the chat and doesn't know. They have been going through a difficult time recently.",prompt1:"What do you do - in the chat, and outside it?",prompt2:"Group dynamics online can make silence feel like consent. Describe a time when you stayed quiet in a group situation - online or in person - and later regretted not speaking up. What stopped you?"},

{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are the eldest sibling in your family. Your parents are ageing and there is an unspoken assumption that you will take on more responsibility for their care than your two younger siblings, who live further away. No one has explicitly agreed to this arrangement. You are starting to feel the weight of it. When you try to raise it with your siblings, one gets defensive and the other promises to help but never follows through.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation in a way that actually moves something forward rather than just releasing your frustration?",prompt2:"Describe a time when an unfair dynamic in a close relationship went unaddressed for a long time because naming it felt too risky. What eventually happened, and do you think you handled it well?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a student who has just been told by your closest university friend that he finds you exhausting to be around when you're stressed - that you become controlling, overcritical, and make everything about yourself. He is a kind person and clearly found it hard to say. You didn't see this coming. Your initial reaction is defensive because you genuinely believe you've always been there for him.",prompt1:"What do you say in that moment, and how do you process this feedback honestly?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you received feedback about yourself that was deeply uncomfortable but, looking back, was probably right. How long did it take to accept it, and what changed as a result?"},

{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a team leader at a non-profit. One of your volunteers, Rania, has been an exceptional contributor for two years. Recently she has taken on more hours than anyone else, routinely works past midnight, and has started making small errors she never made before. When you check in with her, she says she's fine and that 'this work matters too much to slow down.' You have noticed she looks physically unwell.",prompt1:"How do you approach this conversation with Rania - and what are you trying to achieve, beyond just solving the immediate performance issue?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you or someone close to you pushed through a period of genuine burnout rather than stopping. What was the cost - and looking back, what should have happened earlier?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a friend group member. Your group of six close friends has a shared social media page where you post photos from events. A friend in the group, Tom, has recently started a relationship with someone most of the group dislikes - not for serious reasons, just a personality clash. Others in the group have started being subtly exclusionary: not inviting the new partner to events and posting photos that frame Tom as single. Tom hasn't said anything but you can tell he's noticed.",prompt1:"Do you say something - to Tom, to the group, or both? Walk through your reasoning.",prompt2:"Social exclusion among friends is often undeclared and deniable. Describe a time you witnessed someone being quietly pushed out of a group. What did you do, and looking back, was that the right call?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a 24-year-old. Your grandmother, who raised you partly when your parents were going through a divorce, has been diagnosed with moderate dementia. She still recognises you but the conversations are different now - she sometimes confuses the past and present. Your visits leave you feeling a mix of grief, love, and a kind of anticipatory loss that you haven't spoken about with anyone.",prompt1:"How are you processing this experience - and what, if anything, do you say to the people close to you about what you're going through?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you experienced a form of grief or loss that didn't have a name or a clear endpoint - not a death, but a slow change in something that mattered deeply. How did you carry that, and who, if anyone, helped you?"},

{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a senior volunteer at a food bank. A new volunteer, Callum, has arrived full of enthusiasm but keeps overstepping - he rearranges storage without asking, gives instructions to other volunteers, and has started telling recipients of the food bank how to better manage their finances. His heart is clearly in the right place and he's physically very helpful. The coordinator has asked you to 'have a word.'",prompt1:"How do you have this conversation with Callum without crushing his enthusiasm?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to deliver feedback to someone whose biggest problem was something they genuinely saw as a strength. How did you frame it, and how did they respond?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are in your third year of university. You have been dating someone for eighteen months. You recently discovered, by accident, that your partner has been hiding a significant debt from you - not asking you for money, not doing anything dishonest toward you, just keeping something major completely secret. When you raise it, they say they were ashamed and were handling it. They are hurt that you 'went through their things' even though you found it by accident. The debt itself is not your problem. The secrecy is.",prompt1:"How do you navigate this conversation - what matters most to you here, and how do you say it?",prompt2:"Describe a time when trust in a close relationship was damaged - not through a dramatic betrayal, but through an accumulation of smaller things. How did you decide whether the relationship was worth repairing, and how did you go about it?"},

{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a residential college student. Your two closest friends in the college have had a serious falling out over an incident that is genuinely murky - each has a believable account and there may be truth in both versions. Each is now asking you to 'be on their side' and has separately implied that staying close to the other person is a betrayal. You value both friendships and don't think either person is simply wrong.",prompt1:"How do you navigate this without losing either friendship - and is it even possible to stay neutral in a genuine conflict between two people you love?",prompt2:"Describe a time when two people you cared about were in conflict and both wanted your loyalty. What did you do, and how did it affect those relationships long term?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are a first-generation university student. Most of your cohort comes from private schools and has family connections in the industry you're hoping to enter. You are starting to notice that a lot of professional networking and opportunity seems to happen through social contexts - dinners, clubs, casual drinks - that cost money and assume a cultural familiarity you don't always have. You feel both frustrated and uncertain about whether you're imagining it.",prompt1:"How do you navigate this practically - and what is the emotional cost of it that most people around you don't see?",prompt2:"Describe a specific moment when you were acutely aware of being an outsider in a room or context where others seemed to belong naturally. What did that feel like, and what did you do with it?"},

{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a project manager. One of your team members, Dev, consistently misses small deadlines in a way that never catastrophically derails a project but creates a pattern of minor delays and last-minute scrambles for the rest of the team. When you've raised it before, Dev apologises sincerely and things improve briefly, then revert. He is otherwise strong, well-liked, and clearly cares. The rest of the team have started working around him in ways that let him avoid accountability.",prompt1:"What's the actual conversation you need to have with Dev - and how is it different from the ones you've already had?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to break a pattern of ineffective feedback with someone - when saying the same thing differently finally produced a different result. What changed?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a university student. You have a casual job at a busy restaurant. Over the past few weeks, you've noticed that your manager is systematically rounding down the hours logged for all casual staff on the roster - never by more than fifteen minutes per shift, but consistently, for everyone. When you mention it to a colleague, they shrug: 'He's been doing it for years - it's not worth the trouble.' You calculate you've lost around $40 over the past month. Other staff have lost similar amounts.",prompt1:"What do you do - and does the small per-person amount change your ethical reasoning about it?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you witnessed a low-level injustice that most people around you treated as normal or not worth acting on. What did you do - and do you think that was right?"},

{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a community organiser running a volunteer-led reading program for primary school kids. Two parents have approached you separately with complaints about each other - one says the other's child is disruptive and affecting the group; the other says the first parent has been making their child feel unwelcome. The kids involved are seven years old and seem unaware of the adult tension. Both parents have suggested they won't continue if the other family stays.",prompt1:"How do you approach both parents - and how do you keep the kids at the centre of this rather than the adults' conflict?",prompt2:"Describe a time when an adult conflict affected children or a group of young people around you. What was done well, what was done poorly, and what should have happened differently?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are 22 and have recently moved cities for university. You are finding it harder to make real friendships than you expected - not because people are unkind, just because everyone seems to already have their people. You are more lonely than you've ever been and are starting to wonder if there is something about you that makes deep connection difficult. You've never felt this way before.",prompt1:"How do you think honestly about this experience - and what do you actually do about the loneliness?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you had to rebuild a sense of belonging from scratch - a new school, city, team, or community. What did you learn about yourself from that experience, and what made the difference?"},

{category:"Professionalism",scenario:"You are a graduate intern at a policy organisation. Your supervisor asks you to write a brief on a policy question where the evidence is genuinely mixed. The organisation has a clear public position on this issue. When you submit a draft that fairly represents the uncertainty in the evidence - including findings that don't support the organisation's position - your supervisor asks you to 'tighten the framing' and remove sections that could be used against the organisation's advocacy goals.",prompt1:"How do you respond - and how do you think about the tension between advocacy and intellectual honesty in professional contexts?",prompt2:"Describe a time when institutional loyalty or group expectations pressured you to present information in a way that felt less than fully honest. What did you do, and how do you evaluate that decision now?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a friend. Your close friend Jamie is applying for a job at a company where you know someone on the hiring panel - not well, but well enough that a word from you could probably help. Jamie asks if you'd be willing to put in a good word. You think Jamie is genuinely talented and a good person. You also know two other applicants who are applying for the same role and who you believe are equally deserving. You weren't asked by anyone to advocate for them.",prompt1:"Do you put in a word for Jamie - and how do you think about the ethics of using personal connections to influence a competitive process, even when you believe the person deserves it?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you benefited from a connection or advantage that others in a similar situation didn't have. How did you feel about it then, and how do you think about it now?"},

{category:"Communication",scenario:"You are a sibling. Your younger sister, 19, has recently started a relationship with someone who is 31. She is clearly happy and speaks about him warmly. Your parents are uncomfortable but haven't said anything directly. She has asked for your honest opinion. You have some concerns - not because of anything specific you can point to, but because the age gap combined with her age and her inexperience makes you uneasy.",prompt1:"What do you actually say to her - walking the line between honesty and respecting her as an adult who can make her own decisions?",prompt2:"Describe a time when someone you care about asked for your honest opinion and you had to decide how much of your real view to share. What did you say, how did they receive it, and do you think you got the balance right?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"The author Ursula K. Le Guin wrote: 'The only thing that makes life possible is permanent, intolerable uncertainty - not knowing what comes next.' A close friend reads this to you and says it makes her feel better about the chaos in her life right now. You find the quote unsettling rather than comforting.",prompt1:"What is your honest reaction to this quote - and what does the gap between your response and your friend's tell you about how differently two people can relate to the same idea?",prompt2:"Describe a period in your own life when uncertainty was not a philosophical concept but a lived daily reality. How did you actually cope with not knowing - and has your relationship with uncertainty changed since then?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"The philosopher Hannah Arendt argued that the greatest evils in history were not committed by monsters - they were committed by ordinary people who simply stopped thinking. You are sitting with a group of friends when one of them shares a social media post mocking a person none of you know personally. Everyone laughs. You find it cruel but say nothing. Later that night, you think about what Arendt wrote.",prompt1:"What stopped you from saying something in the moment - and how honest are you willing to be about that?",prompt2:"Arendt's point is that passivity and thoughtlessness are not neutral. Do you think that applies to the moment in that room - and what, if anything, does that ask of you now?"},

{category:"Conflict Resolution",scenario:"You are a close friend. Your friend group of five has a running joke that has evolved over years - it started harmless but has slowly become more pointed and is now clearly aimed at one member of the group, Lena, who always laughs along. Last week, after the group left, Lena texted you privately: 'Sometimes I wonder if they actually like me.' She has not asked you to do anything about it and you are not sure she wants you to.",prompt1:"What do you do with that message - and how do you think about the difference between what Lena asked for and what she might actually need?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you were part of a group dynamic that you could see was slowly causing harm to someone, but where the harm was hard to name because it was wrapped in humour or familiarity. What did you do - and what do you wish you had done?"},

{category:"Personal",scenario:"You are given an unusual task: write your own eulogy - not as you hope to be remembered, but as you honestly believe you would be remembered if you died today. You don't have to share it with anyone.",prompt1:"What does that eulogy actually say - and what is the gap between that version and the one you would want written?",prompt2:"Most people find this exercise uncomfortable not because they have done terrible things, but because the gap between who they are and who they want to be is larger than they admit day to day. What is the one thing you would need to change to close that gap - and what has stopped you from changing it already?"},

{category:"Ethics",scenario:"You are a volunteer coordinator. Your organisation runs a weekly meal program for people experiencing homelessness. One evening, after service ends, you notice that one of your longest-serving volunteers - a warm, well-liked man named Arthur - has been quietly pocketing small amounts of leftover donated food at the end of every shift: a piece of fruit, a bread roll, sometimes a small container of soup. He hasn't hidden it exactly, but he hasn't drawn attention to it either. You later learn from another volunteer that Arthur lost his job three months ago and is quietly struggling himself.",prompt1:"What do you do - and does knowing about Arthur's situation change your ethical reasoning, or does it only change how you feel about it?",prompt2:"Describe a time when you discovered that someone you respected had done something that was technically wrong but came from a place of genuine need. How did you reconcile the two things - and what did you decide?"}

];


const MMI_STATIONS=[
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"You have decided to pursue medicine. Beyond the standard answers, reflect honestly on what is actually driving that decision — and what it has cost you or changed about you to get here.","prompt1":"Why do you want to study medicine?","prompt2":"What has your path to this interview taught you about yourself?","prompt3":"You've given me your reasons for wanting to study medicine - now convince me why medicine needs you specifically. What unique perspective or capability do you bring that other candidates don't?","prompt4":"Imagine you're 10 years into your medical career and you're having doubts about whether you made the right choice. What would you tell your younger self sitting here today, and what would you need to hear to recommit?","prompt5":"Ten years from now, if a patient you have cared for were asked to describe the kind of doctor you are — not your clinical skills but your character — what would you want them to say, and how are you actively becoming that person today?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"You have significant volunteer work in your background. Strip away what you were supposed to learn from it — think about what actually surprised you, or changed how you see people, or changed how you see yourself.","prompt1":"What did your volunteer experience genuinely teach you?","prompt2":"How has it shaped what kind of doctor you want to be?","prompt3":"You say volunteering changed how you think about medicine, but I'm skeptical - most students say exactly that. Give me one specific moment where you genuinely questioned something you believed before, not just felt good about helping.","prompt4":"Now flip this around - what did you observe about the healthcare system or patient care during your volunteering that actually worried you or made you uncomfortable?","prompt5":"Most doctors encounter moments early in training where the reality of the job does not match what drew them to medicine. What do you think your moment will be — and what will carry you through it?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Think of a time you were responsible for something — a group, a project, a situation — and you got it wrong. Not a mistake that only affected you, but a failure of responsibility toward others.","prompt1":"What happened, and what was your role in it?","prompt2":"What did the people affected experience — and did you ever actually find out?","prompt3":"How did you handle the accountability — and is there a gap between what you said you felt and what you actually did?","prompt4":"Medicine will put you in charge of things before you feel ready. What does this experience tell you about how you carry responsibility?","prompt5":"If the people you let down were asked to describe how you handled it afterwards, what would they say — and would you agree with their account?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Medicine is full of situations where you will not know the answer, where the evidence is unclear, and where reasonable people disagree. Reflect honestly on your relationship with uncertainty.","prompt1":"How do you personally relate to uncertainty - intellectually and emotionally?","prompt2":"Give me a specific example of a time you had to act or make a decision under genuine uncertainty - where the right answer wasn't clear and the stakes were real. What did you do, and what did it teach you?","prompt3":"You've described how you handle uncertainty, but let's be honest - most medical students I interview say they're 'comfortable with uncertainty' yet struggle when they actually face it. What makes you think you'll be different when a patient is deteriorating and you genuinely don't know what's wrong?","prompt4":"Think about the healthcare system more broadly - how should we train doctors to make decisions when evidence is limited or conflicting, and how do we balance admitting uncertainty with maintaining patient confidence?","prompt5":"Think of a doctor you admire — real or fictional. How do they handle uncertainty, and in what ways do you want to be like them, and unlike them?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Think of a time you encountered suffering — not in a clinical setting, just in life — and what it asked of you.","prompt1":"Describe the experience and how you responded.","prompt2":"Looking back, is there anything you wish you had done differently - and what does that reflection tell you about the kind of practitioner you want to become?","prompt3":"You've told me what you learned about yourself, but what did that experience teach you about the person who was suffering - and how will that shape how you listen to patients who are in pain?","prompt4":"Think about your response in that moment - walk me through your actual thought process as it was happening, not the neat story you've constructed afterwards.","prompt5":"Some doctors describe becoming less affected by suffering over time — desensitised. Others say the opposite. Which do you think is more dangerous for patients, and what does that tell you about how you want to practise?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Medicine will ask you to see people at their most vulnerable every single day. Think about what in your background has actually prepared you for that — not in theory, but in practice.","prompt1":"What experiences have genuinely prepared you for sustained exposure to human suffering and vulnerability?","prompt2":"Describe a specific moment when someone was at their most vulnerable in front of you - not a clinical moment, just a human one - and tell me what you did, and what it asked of you emotionally.","prompt3":"You've told me about handling vulnerability in others, but medicine will also expose your own vulnerabilities - your mistakes, your limitations, your emotional breaking points. What makes you think you can handle being that exposed yourself?","prompt4":"Take that specific vulnerable moment you described and imagine you had to witness fifty similar situations in a single week, then go home to your family and be present for them. Walk me through how you'd actually manage that transition.","prompt5":"If a patient sees through your professional composure — catches you in a moment of genuine distress or uncertainty — what do you do? And is that a failure?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Strip away the status, the difficulty, the prestige of a medical degree. Think about why you actually want this, really.","prompt1":"What is your honest, unguarded answer for why you want to be a doctor?","prompt2":"What would it mean to you personally - not professionally - to become one?","prompt3":"Tell me about a moment when you seriously considered not pursuing medicine - what pulled you back?","prompt4":"If you had to convince a burnt-out doctor why this career is still worth it, what would you say?","prompt5":"Describe a specific moment — not a general theme, a specific moment — when you knew medicine was what you wanted. What was happening, and why did it land the way it did?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"You are about to begin a medical degree. You have worked hard to get here. But you are also aware that people who look like you, come from your background, or had access to what you had are significantly overrepresented in medicine — and that the path that felt like a meritocracy was not entirely one.","prompt1":"How do you sit with that honestly — without either dismissing it or drowning in it?","prompt2":"What do you think you owe to the people who did not get the same access you did — and is \"working hard as a doctor\" a sufficient answer?","prompt3":"If someone told you that your place should have gone to a more disadvantaged candidate with similar scores, how would you respond — honestly, not ideally?","prompt4":"How does awareness of your own privilege change, if at all, what kind of doctor you want to be?","prompt5":"What would it mean to use this degree in a way that actively works against the conditions that made it easier for you than for others — and are you willing to do that?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a medical student on placement. You observe your supervising consultant dismiss a patient's concerns about a proposed treatment with visible impatience, saying 'Trust me, I've done this a thousand times.' The patient looks uncertain but says nothing more. The treatment plan proceeds.","prompt1":"What are your thoughts on what just happened?","prompt2":"What, if anything, would you do - and how do you weigh speaking up against the risk of undermining a senior colleague?","prompt3":"You've identified concerns about informed consent and patient autonomy, but some would argue that excessive explanation can actually harm patients by creating unnecessary anxiety about procedures with minimal risk. How do you respond to this view?","prompt4":"Imagine this exact scenario happens again next week with a different patient. Walk me through your specific actions in the first two minutes after witnessing it.","prompt5":"How do you think that patient is feeling right now — and what, if anything, can you do for them in the next five minutes?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"A terminally ill patient, fully lucid, asks you to help her die. You are in a jurisdiction where voluntary assisted dying is legal and she meets the criteria. However, it is against your personal beliefs.","prompt1":"How do you navigate this?","prompt2":"Is conscientious objection ever an acceptable response in medicine - and if so, where are its limits?","prompt3":"You've decided to refer her to another doctor who will help her die, but she says 'I trust you, not some stranger - please don't abandon me now.' How do you respond to her plea?","prompt4":"Imagine you're this patient's daughter watching your mother suffer while her doctor wrestles with personal beliefs. What would you want that doctor to prioritize?","prompt5":"If there were no legal framework for assisted dying in your jurisdiction — if this patient had no options at all — what would your obligations be then, and how does legality shape your ethics versus your conscience?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor and you make a medication error that, fortunately, does not harm the patient. You correct it before anyone else notices. You are now wondering whether to disclose it.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"What does a culture of disclosure actually require from individual practitioners - and what does it require from institutions?","prompt3":"Think about a time you've been asked to bend the truth in a 'harmless' way - how is this medical situation similar or different to that experience?","prompt4":"If reporting this error would trigger a formal investigation that could delay your career progression by months, does your answer change?","prompt5":"Imagine you report this error and it leads to a formal investigation with real career consequences. Looking back from that future, do you still think disclosure was the right call — and does your answer tell you something important about yourself?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"A 14-year-old presents to your GP clinic asking for contraception. She does not want her parents told. She appears mature and understands what she is asking for.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"How do you think about a young person's right to make their own medical decisions — and where are the limits of that right?","prompt3":"Three months later she returns, still without parental involvement, but now asking about a termination. How does your thinking change as the stakes escalate?","prompt4":"Now imagine you're the parent who discovers their 14-year-old has been accessing reproductive health services without your knowledge. How do you balance respecting your child's autonomy with your parental responsibilities?","prompt5":"What would it mean to this young woman if you refused her request — and how does imagining that consequence shape how you think about the clinical decision?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a junior doctor on a busy surgical ward. The ward clerk - a long-standing staff member who is well-liked - has been consistently prioritising certain patients' discharge paperwork over others in a way that delays discharges for patients from a particular cultural background. You are not certain this is intentional.","prompt1":"How do you approach this situation?","prompt2":"How do you address a pattern of behaviour that may or may not be deliberate - when raising it risks labelling someone unfairly, but not raising it risks harm continuing?","prompt3":"A senior nurse tells you she's noticed the same pattern but warns that the ward clerk has powerful allies in administration who could make your life difficult if you push this. What do you do now?","prompt4":"Think about a time when you might have unconsciously treated people differently based on assumptions. How does that experience inform your approach here?","prompt5":"If you raise this concern and it turns out the pattern was coincidental, how do you maintain your relationship with the ward clerk — and with yourself, given you reported someone who was innocent?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"Your study group of five is preparing for finals. One member has suggested you all pool and share answers to past exam questions. The document is now also including specific questions that he says he 'heard were definitely on the paper from someone who did it last year.' Two members are enthusiastic. Two are uncomfortable. Everyone is looking at you.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"How do group dynamics make it harder to act on your values in these situations - and what does it take to hold your position when the group is moving in a different direction?","prompt3":"You decide to speak up against using the leaked questions, but the two enthusiastic members accuse you of being self-righteous and say you're jeopardizing everyone's chances when 'everyone else is probably doing this too.' How do you respond to their pushback?","prompt4":"Imagine you're now the Dean reviewing this situation after it's been reported - what factors would you weigh in deciding consequences, and how would you balance individual accountability versus the systemic pressures students face?","prompt5":"If you had already looked at the leaked questions before realising they were potentially from the real paper, what would you do — and does the order of events change your culpability?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a resident. Your registrar, whom you respect and have a good relationship with, gives you feedback after a ward round that you felt was inaccurate and publicly delivered in a way that was humiliating. Other team members were present. You are still processing it.","prompt1":"How do you handle this?","prompt2":"What is the difference between feedback that is hard to hear and feedback that is genuinely unfair - and how do you respond to each?","prompt3":"You decide to approach your registrar privately about this feedback. They respond defensively, saying you're being oversensitive and that this is just how medicine works. How do you proceed?","prompt4":"Think about a time when you gave someone feedback that didn't land well. What would you want that person to do, and how does that inform your approach here?","prompt5":"How do you ensure this experience makes you a better teacher yourself — what specific commitment do you make about the way you will give feedback when you are the senior person in the room?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are part of a multidisciplinary team managing an elderly patient's care. The patient's son - who has medical power of attorney - is insisting on continuing aggressive treatment. The medical team, the palliative care team, and the nursing staff all believe further intervention is futile and causing suffering. The patient has not been able to express her wishes for some time.","prompt1":"How should this be managed?","prompt2":"What is the ethical and human weight of a medical power of attorney - and what happens when the person holding it is making decisions the team believes are not in the patient's interests?","prompt3":"You've outlined your approach, but now the son reveals he's a doctor himself and accuses your team of giving up too early because his mother is elderly. How do you respond to his expertise challenge while maintaining your position?","prompt4":"Step back from being the healthcare provider - imagine you're the patient's daughter watching this unfold between your brother and the medical team. What would you want to happen?","prompt5":"If this situation ends with the patient dying in a way the team believes was unnecessarily prolonged, what does each person in that room carry — and what does that tell you about decision-making in medicine?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a GP. Two of your long-term patients are a married couple. You have been seeing them separately for years. The husband comes to you and discloses that he has had an affair and has a sexually transmitted infection. He begs you not to tell his wife, who is also your patient.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"How do you manage ongoing care of both patients in a way that is ethical, when your knowledge of one affects your obligations to the other?","prompt3":"The husband threatens to change doctors and take his wife with him if you breach his confidentiality, potentially leaving them both without proper medical care. Does this change your approach?","prompt4":"Three months later, the wife comes in asking why you keep suggesting STI screening when she's been monogamous - how do you handle this conversation without lying?","prompt5":"How do you continue being an effective GP for both of them over the next year — and is there a point at which you would recommend one of them find another doctor?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a medical student on placement. You witness a nurse administer what you believe to be the wrong dose of a medication to a patient. You are not certain - you could have misread the chart. The nurse has 20 years of experience and you have been on the ward for two weeks.","prompt1":"What do you do in this moment?","prompt2":"How does your level of certainty affect your obligation to act - and what is the cost of getting this wrong in either direction?","prompt3":"The nurse later pulls you aside and says 'I've been doing this for two decades, and students like you questioning me undermines patient trust in the whole team.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"Imagine you're now the experienced nurse in this scenario, and a medical student approaches you with concerns about your medication administration. What would you want them to say and do?","prompt5":"How does this experience change how you will approach situations of uncertainty for the rest of your career — and what is the cost of becoming someone who always escalates versus someone who learns to tolerate uncertainty?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A colleague - a registrar you work closely with - has been coming in smelling of alcohol on morning shifts. No patient has been harmed. When you raise it privately, he says he's going through a divorce and asks you to keep it between you.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"What does a doctor's duty of care extend to - and does it include other members of the team?","prompt3":"Two weeks later, you notice the same colleague making a medication error that could have been serious. How does this change your approach, and what specific actions will you take in the next 24 hours?","prompt4":"Think about a time when someone trusted you with sensitive information that put you in a difficult position. How do the principles you used then apply here, and where might they differ?","prompt5":"If you do everything right — report appropriately, follow up, act with care — and your colleague loses their career as a result, how do you process that outcome?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a senior medical student. You have been assigned to present a case to the team. After your presentation, the consultant - in front of the whole team - tells you your assessment was 'exactly the kind of sloppy thinking that gets patients killed.' Your assessment was, in fact, correct.","prompt1":"How do you respond in that moment?","prompt2":"What does this experience reveal about the culture of medicine - and how do you preserve your sense of self in environments that use humiliation as a teaching tool?","prompt3":"Six months later, you're now the consultant and witness a colleague doing exactly what happened to you - publicly humiliating a correct student. What do you do, and how do you balance your duty to the student against potential career consequences of challenging a peer?","prompt4":"You mentioned preserving your sense of self - but what if staying true to yourself means you can't function in this system? At what point would you consider that medicine itself might not be worth the psychological cost?","prompt5":"Is there any version of public correction in medicine that is acceptable — and if so, what does it look like? Draw the line precisely."},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a GP. A patient's family contacts you outside of normal channels, asking you to share the patient's medical information and to consider changing his treatment plan. The patient - a 70-year-old man - has capacity and has explicitly told you he does not want his family involved in his care.","prompt1":"How do you respond to the family?","prompt2":"What does this situation reveal about the tension between family-centred and patient-centred care - and who gets to decide?","prompt3":"The family argues they know what's 'really best' for their father and that his refusal to involve them proves he's not thinking clearly. How do you respond to this challenge to his capacity?","prompt4":"Imagine you're the 70-year-old patient who discovers his family contacted you behind his back. What would this mean for your trust in both your doctor and your family?","prompt5":"How do you bring up with your patient that his family contacted you — and do you have to? Walk me through the exact conversation."},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"There is a growing movement to introduce a sugar tax in Australia - a levy on sugary drinks - as a public health measure to reduce obesity and type 2 diabetes.","prompt1":"What are the arguments for and against a sugar tax as a public health intervention?","prompt2":"When is it appropriate for governments to use taxation to influence health behaviour - and where should the line be drawn?","prompt3":"You've likely supported some form of government intervention here - but what if I told you that sugar taxes disproportionately burden low-income families who spend a higher percentage of their income on food, essentially making healthy choices a privilege of the wealthy?","prompt4":"Walk me through exactly how you would design and implement a sugar tax policy in Australia - what specific products, what tax rate, and how would you measure success in the first year?","prompt5":"A patient in your clinic drinks two litres of soft drink a day and refuses to change. You have told them the health consequences clearly. At what point, if any, does individual choice stop being something medicine can respect — and what does your answer imply for public health policy?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"A major Australian hospital is considering introducing a policy of mandatory drug and alcohol testing for all clinical staff before each shift. The policy has been proposed following two incidents involving impaired clinicians. Unions are strongly opposed.","prompt1":"What are the key considerations for and against this policy?","prompt2":"How do you balance patient safety with the rights and wellbeing of healthcare workers?","prompt3":"If you were the hospital's chief medical officer and the union threatened to strike over this policy, potentially leaving the hospital understaffed, what would you do?","prompt4":"How might similar mandatory testing policies affect other high-stakes professions like pilots or teachers, and what does this tell us about healthcare's unique responsibilities?","prompt5":"If mandatory testing detected a nurse who was impaired but had delivered safe care for six months — and termination ended her career — what does that outcome reveal about what the policy is actually optimising for?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"Australia's Medicare system funds GP consultations at a rate that many argue is too low to sustain bulk billing, leading to out-of-pocket costs that are highest for the people who can least afford them.","prompt1":"What are the systemic causes of declining bulk billing, and what would a fair solution look like?","prompt2":"How do you think about equity in healthcare access - and whose responsibility is it to ensure it?","prompt3":"You've outlined what should happen, but if you were the Health Minister with a fixed budget and powerful lobbying from both the AMA and patient advocacy groups, what specific trade-offs would you actually make?","prompt4":"Think about your own family's healthcare decisions over the past few years - how has cost influenced where you've sought care, and what does that tell you about your position on this issue?","prompt5":"If you were a GP who could not afford to bulk bill and were seeing patients pay $80 out of pocket, how would you reconcile that reality with the values that brought you to medicine?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"There is an ongoing debate about whether voluntary assisted dying should be further expanded in Australia - including for people with treatment-resistant mental illness, not just terminal physical illness.","prompt1":"What are the strongest arguments on each side of this debate?","prompt2":"How do you hold a personal view on a deeply contested moral question while remaining able to practise ethically across a diverse patient population?","prompt3":"If you were designing the policy framework for this expansion, what specific safeguards would you implement to prevent coercion while respecting patient autonomy?","prompt4":"How might Indigenous Australian perspectives on mental health, healing, and end-of-life decisions challenge or enrich the predominantly Western biomedical framework driving this debate?","prompt5":"A patient with treatment-resistant depression who meets every proposed safeguard is sitting in front of you requesting assisted dying. You believe they are suffering genuinely. Walk me through your actual thought process in that room."},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"Preventive medicine - stopping disease before it starts - is consistently underfunded compared to acute care in Australia.","prompt1":"Why is preventive medicine chronically underfunded, and what are the structural barriers to changing that?","prompt2":"If you were advising a health minister, what one policy change would you prioritise and why?","prompt3":"You've argued for more preventive funding, but critics say it's just politicians spending money on feel-good programs with no measurable short-term results that voters care about. How do you respond to that charge?","prompt4":"Think about your own healthcare choices over the past year - when did you prioritise prevention versus waiting for problems to emerge, and what drove those decisions?","prompt5":"As a future clinician, what preventive practice will you embed in every patient encounter — not as an add-on, but as a core clinical behaviour — and how will you sustain it under time pressure?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"Australia has a significant and well-documented gap in health outcomes between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians. This gap has persisted despite decades of policy attention.","prompt1":"What are the root causes of the Indigenous health gap in Australia, and why have existing policies fallen short?","prompt2":"What do you think is actually required - structurally and culturally - to close it?","prompt3":"If you were Health Minister and had to choose just one intervention to fund for the next decade, what would it be and how would you measure whether it's actually working?","prompt4":"Indigenous health advocates argue that well-meaning non-Indigenous doctors often perpetuate the problem despite good intentions. How might your own background limit your effectiveness in this space?","prompt5":"You are a non-Indigenous doctor working in a remote community. A community elder tells you directly: 'You are not the right person to be making decisions about our health.' How do you respond — and what does that moment ask of you?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"There is growing evidence that social determinants - housing, income, education, food security - account for more of the variation in health outcomes than access to healthcare itself.","prompt1":"What does this evidence suggest about how we should allocate health resources?","prompt2":"What is the appropriate role of doctors and health systems in addressing factors that lie outside their traditional domain?","prompt3":"If you were Australia's Health Minister and had to cut either hospital funding or social housing investment by 20%, which would you choose and why?","prompt4":"Some argue that doctors focusing on social issues is 'mission creep' that distracts from clinical excellence - how do you respond to this criticism?","prompt5":"A patient who is homeless presents with a manageable chronic condition. You treat them and discharge them back to the street. What is the honest limit of what medicine can do here — and how do you sit with that?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"Private health insurance in Australia is in structural decline, with younger and healthier people dropping cover. This places increasing pressure on the public system.","prompt1":"What are the consequences of this trend, and what should be done about it?","prompt2":"Is a two-tier healthcare system - one for those who can pay, one for those who can't - ethically defensible?","prompt3":"You're Minister for Health and need to announce a policy tomorrow that will reverse this trend within 5 years. What specific intervention do you implement, and how do you sell it to voters who'll pay for it?","prompt4":"Reflect on how your own family's financial situation has shaped your views on healthcare access. How might someone from a completely different economic background see this issue?","prompt5":"You are treating two patients with the same condition — one private, one public. The private patient gets their procedure in two weeks; the public patient waits eight months. You are the same doctor for both. What does that feel like, and what do you do with that feeling?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"The COVID-19 pandemic revealed significant gaps in Australia's public health infrastructure - surveillance systems, supply chains, pandemic planning, and health workforce capacity.","prompt1":"What should Australia have learned from COVID-19, and what systemic changes should have followed?","prompt2":"Why do you think many of those lessons remain unimplemented - and what does that reveal about how health policy is actually made?","prompt3":"You've identified barriers to implementing pandemic lessons - now defend the opposing view: why might deliberate inaction or slow implementation actually be the rational policy choice here?","prompt4":"Take your pandemic preparedness principles and apply them to climate-related health threats - do the same systemic changes work, or does this reveal gaps in your thinking?","prompt5":"You are a junior doctor during the next pandemic. Your hospital is overwhelmed, PPE is rationed, and you are being asked to work in conditions you consider unsafe. What do you do?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"There is a strong evidence base for harm reduction approaches to drug policy - needle exchanges, safe injecting facilities, decriminalisation of personal possession. These approaches remain politically contested in Australia.","prompt1":"What is your view on harm reduction as a framework for drug policy?","prompt2":"How do you communicate a position grounded in evidence to a community or patient group that holds strong moral objections to it?","prompt3":"You're now Health Minister and polling shows 70% of voters oppose safe injecting rooms despite the evidence you've presented. Do you proceed with implementation anyway, and how do you justify overriding public opinion?","prompt4":"Think about how you just approached this evidence-versus-values tension. What does your reasoning process reveal about how you weigh scientific data against community sentiment in healthcare decisions?","prompt5":"A patient tells you they use heroin and have no interest in stopping. They want clean needles and wound care. What is your job in this consultation — and what does your answer reveal about your values as a clinician?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"Think about your greatest personal achievement — not your most impressive credential, but the thing you are genuinely most proud of, and why.","prompt1":"What is your greatest achievement, and why does it matter to you personally?","prompt2":"What did that experience teach you about yourself that you couldn't have learned any other way?","prompt3":"Most people describe achievements that involved overcoming something. What specifically did you have to overcome, and is there any part of you that doubts whether it was really that hard?","prompt4":"What does that achievement require of the person you are becoming — and is that a version of yourself you are actively working toward?","prompt5":"If that achievement were stripped from your identity — if you could not mention it, think about it, or reference it — what would remain that you are proud of?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"Think of an actual failure — not a minor inconvenience you turned into a lesson, but a moment where you let yourself or someone else down and the outcome mattered.","prompt1":"Describe the failure.","prompt2":"What did you do after, and how did it change you?","prompt3":"Looking back now, was the failure ultimately yours, someone else's, or the system's - and does that distinction matter?","prompt4":"Medicine will involve failures that cannot be fixed and patients you cannot save. How does the way you handled that experience prepare you for that?","prompt5":"How do you talk about this failure with people who matter to you — or do you? What does your answer reveal about how comfortable you are with imperfection?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"Think of a time you genuinely understood something about another person's experience that was very different from your own — not what you were supposed to feel, but what you actually felt.","prompt1":"Tell me about that experience.","prompt2":"How did it change the way you see that group of people, or that situation?","prompt3":"Is there a group of people whose perspective you find genuinely difficult to understand or empathise with? What makes it hard?","prompt4":"Empathy in medicine can be emotionally costly. How do you plan to sustain it without burning out?","prompt5":"Describe a person whose life experience is so different from yours that empathy feels genuinely effortful — not impossible, but requiring real work. What makes it hard, and what do you do about that?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"Think of a time you received feedback that was difficult to hear — and later realised it was completely right. Walk through your initial reaction, your reflection, and what actually changed.","prompt1":"What was the feedback, and what was your first reaction?","prompt2":"What changed your mind - and what did you actually do differently as a result?","prompt3":"Is there feedback you have received that you still disagree with, even now? How do you hold that?","prompt4":"How do you intend to seek out feedback as a medical student and doctor, given that honest feedback in medicine is notoriously difficult to get?","prompt5":"How do you distinguish between feedback that is hard because it is true, and feedback that is hard because it is wrong? Give me a concrete example of each from your own experience."},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"Think of a time you had to work with someone you genuinely disliked or found very difficult — not a minor irritant, but someone whose presence consistently made things harder for you.","prompt1":"What made them difficult for you - and how did you manage it?","prompt2":"Looking back, was any of their behaviour understandable, even if it was still difficult?","prompt3":"Medicine involves working closely with colleagues and patients you may find challenging. What do you do when professional obligation and personal feeling are in direct conflict?","prompt4":"What did that experience teach you about yourself - particularly about your own triggers or blind spots?","prompt5":"What do you do when you realise your personal feelings about someone are starting to affect the quality of your work — and how will you manage that as a doctor when you cannot choose your patients?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"You are a medical student on a ward. A patient you have been asked to take a brief history from becomes angry almost immediately. He tells you to get out, says he is sick of students practising on him, and that no one has told him anything about his own condition for three days.","prompt1":"What do you do in that moment — not the ideal response, the real one?","prompt2":"His anger is directed at you, but it is clearly not really about you. How do you hold that distinction when someone is being hostile?","prompt3":"He calms slightly and says: \"No one actually listens. You probably won't either.\" What do you say?","prompt4":"After the encounter, what do you do about the fact that he has not been informed about his condition for three days?","prompt5":"How do you take care of yourself after a difficult interaction like this — and what does your answer reveal about your capacity to stay present for the next patient?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a medical student on placement. During a handover, you overhear a registrar joking with nurses about a patient's weight, using language that is clearly mocking. The patient is in the next room with the curtain partially open. The registrar is known for excellent clinical care and is generally well-regarded by the team.","prompt1":"What do you do in this moment?","prompt2":"How do you weigh the discomfort of saying something against the harm of saying nothing?","prompt3":"The registrar responds to your concern by saying the patient couldn't have heard and it was just team stress relief. How do you respond?","prompt4":"How does this kind of language, even when patients don't hear it, affect the culture of care on a ward?","prompt5":"If this kind of language is endemic on the ward — not one incident but a culture — what is your realistic capacity to change it as a junior person, and what is the cost of trying?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. You have noticed over several weeks that a scrub nurse on your surgical team - someone who is liked by everyone and has an impeccable reputation - appears to be pocketing unused controlled drug ampoules at the end of procedures rather than discarding them in the witness-disposal process. She does not appear impaired at work. You have not directly confronted her, and you are not entirely certain of what you have seen.","prompt1":"What do you do, and how does your level of certainty affect your decision?","prompt2":"What are the competing obligations here - to the nurse, to patients, to the team, and to the institution?","prompt3":"You report your concern to your supervisor, who thanks you and says they will 'look into it.' Two weeks later, nothing seems to have changed. What do you do now?","prompt4":"If it turns out you were wrong and the nurse was following protocol correctly, and she now knows you reported her - how do you handle that professionally and personally?","prompt5":"If the investigation reveals she was self-medicating due to untreated chronic pain she could not take time off work for — how does that context change your feelings about the outcome, and does it change anything about what was right to do?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a medical student. A fellow student - someone you are close to - tells you in confidence that they cheated on a written exam by photographing pages of the exam paper and sharing them with two other students. They are not asking for advice. They are telling you because they feel guilty and need to talk. They ask you to keep it between you.","prompt1":"What do you do - and does the fact that they told you in confidence change your obligation?","prompt2":"What is at stake here beyond this individual incident - for the integrity of the assessment, for other students, and for future patients?","prompt3":"Your friend says: 'You're acting like I murdered someone - it was just one exam.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"If you decide to report it, how do you manage the end of that friendship - and are you prepared for that cost?","prompt5":"Imagine this classmate becomes a doctor and makes an error years from now. You will never know whether the habits formed during training contributed. How do you live with the uncertainty of what your silence or action today meant downstream?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A well-respected and senior consultant - someone who has mentored you - comes back from lunch on a Tuesday and you notice his speech is slightly slurred, his eyes are glassy, and he moves with unusual deliberateness. He sees patients that afternoon. A nurse quietly mentions to you that she has noticed he smells of alcohol sometimes after lunch, 'but he's always been fine.' No patient has been harmed.","prompt1":"What do you do - right now, today?","prompt2":"How does his seniority, his mentorship of you, and his otherwise strong record affect what you are obligated to do?","prompt3":"You raise a concern with the clinical director, who asks you: 'Are you absolutely certain? Because this man has given 25 years to this hospital.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What does a genuine culture of patient safety require of individual doctors - and what makes that requirement so difficult to act on in practice?","prompt5":"If you report this and are wrong — his behaviour had an innocent explanation — and it damages both his career and your relationship with him irreparably, how do you evaluate that outcome?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a GP. A teenage patient - 16 years old - comes to see you for a check-up. During the consultation he discloses, casually, that he has been vaping daily for about a year. He asks you not to tell his parents. He is otherwise healthy, engaged in school, and appears genuinely well. His parents are waiting in the waiting room.","prompt1":"How do you handle this consultation?","prompt2":"What is your ethical and clinical obligation here - both to him and to his parents?","prompt3":"He says: 'If you tell them I'll never come back to a doctor.' How do you weigh his engagement with healthcare against the need for parental awareness?","prompt4":"How does Australia's framework around adolescent confidentiality shape what you can and can't do here?","prompt5":"He comes back six months later with a more serious health disclosure and says he is only telling you because you handled the vaping conversation well. What does that moment tell you about the long-term consequences of clinical decisions that feel small at the time?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a medical student. During a clinical placement, a patient asks you to keep a secret. She tells you she has been taking herbal supplements that interact with her prescribed medications - she hasn't told her treating team because she is afraid of being judged. She adds: 'I know you're just a student - I trust you more than the doctors because you actually listen.'","prompt1":"How do you respond to her in this moment?","prompt2":"What are your obligations as a student in this situation - and how are they different from a qualified doctor's obligations?","prompt3":"She becomes upset when you explain you may need to share this information. She says, 'I knew I shouldn't have said anything.' How do you repair this moment?","prompt4":"What does this interaction tell you about why patients sometimes trust students more than consultants - and what responsibility does that create for you?","prompt5":"How do you think the way you handle this moment shapes this patient's relationship with the healthcare system for years to come — and what does that responsibility ask of you as a student?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A colleague shows you a social media post - anonymous, on a forum used by junior doctors - that accurately describes a patient's unusual case in enough detail that staff who were involved would recognise it. The post is not malicious; the doctor seems to be venting about a frustrating clinical decision. No name or hospital is identified explicitly.","prompt1":"Is this an ethical breach - and how serious is it?","prompt2":"What would you do, and what factors make this harder than it seems?","prompt3":"The colleague who showed you says: 'I do this all the time - it's how we decompress. You're being precious.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"How do you think social media is changing medical professionalism - and what standards should medical students and doctors hold themselves to?","prompt5":"What should medical schools be doing to prepare students for professional use of social media — and what is currently missing from that preparation?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a final-year medical student. A patient on your ward - a 45-year-old man who has been told he has a serious diagnosis - grabs your arm as you walk past and says quietly: 'I need you to tell me the truth. Am I dying?' You are not his doctor. You have read his file. The prognosis is poor. His treating team has not yet had the full discussion with him.","prompt1":"What do you say to him right now?","prompt2":"What are the boundaries of a student's role here - and how do you hold them without abandoning him?","prompt3":"He says: 'The doctors keep brushing me off. You're the only one who actually talks to me.' How does this change how you feel - and does it change what you do?","prompt4":"What does this moment tell you about communication in hospitals and what patients actually need?","prompt5":"What does this moment tell you about the gap between what patients need and what the hospital system is designed to provide — and what role does the student play in bridging it?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. You discover that a colleague has been falsifying records of a minor clinical audit - marking tasks as completed that were not done. It has not led to any patient harm. When you raise it with them privately, they become upset and say they were overwhelmed, they haven't slept properly in weeks, and it will never happen again.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"How do you separate the human situation from the professional obligation?","prompt3":"Your colleague says: 'If you report this, my career is over - and you know how hard this job is right now.' How do you respond to that appeal?","prompt4":"What does this situation reveal about the systems that produce falsified documentation - and does that reduce individual accountability?","prompt5":"How do you distinguish between a culture that produces falsified documentation and an individual who simply chose dishonesty — and does that distinction change what you do?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a medical student in a GP clinic. An older woman comes in for a prescription renewal. While the GP steps out, she confides to you that she gave half of last month's supply of her sleeping tablets to her neighbour, who 'was having a terrible time and couldn't sleep.' She doesn't think it's a big deal. She expects you not to mention it.","prompt1":"What do you say to her in this moment?","prompt2":"What are the clinical, legal, and ethical dimensions of what she has described?","prompt3":"She says: 'I was just being kind. Are you really going to get me in trouble for helping a friend?' How do you hold this tension?","prompt4":"What do you tell the GP when they return - and how do you frame it?","prompt5":"What does this interaction reveal about how patients conceptualise medication safety — and how do you communicate genuine risk without making her feel criminalised for an act she experienced as kindness?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. You are reviewing a patient who has signed a DNR order. During a routine check, the patient - who has capacity and is lucid - pulls you close and says: 'I've changed my mind. I want everything done.' His family is in the room and immediately begins saying: 'No, Dad - we talked about this. This is what you wanted.'","prompt1":"What do you do immediately?","prompt2":"How do you navigate the family's involvement when the patient himself is speaking clearly and has capacity?","prompt3":"The family asks you privately to 'just ignore it - he says this every few days and then forgets.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What does this situation tell you about DNR conversations and how and when they should be revisited?","prompt5":"What would you want if you were the patient in this scenario — and how does imagining yourself in that bed change how you approach the decision?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a medical student. A classmate asks to copy your notes from a lecture you both attended but she slept through due to a family emergency. You say yes. A week later she asks again - a different lecture, a different reason. Over the next month, this becomes a pattern. She is now asking you for your assignment notes 'just to check structure.' The line is moving.","prompt1":"At what point, if any, does sharing notes become academically problematic - and have you already crossed it?","prompt2":"How do you have the conversation with her that resets the boundary?","prompt3":"She says: 'You've always helped me before - why are you being difficult now?' How do you hold your position without damaging the friendship?","prompt4":"How does this dynamic - where individual favours accumulate into something you didn't agree to - connect to situations you might face in medicine?","prompt5":"How do you think about the relationship between small compromises and larger ones — and what principle do you use to know when a line has been crossed?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a medical student on a group project worth 40% of your grade. One member, despite multiple reminders, has contributed almost nothing. The submission is in 48 hours. The rest of the group wants to submit without his name on it. He has personal issues you are aware of but that the group doesn't know about.","prompt1":"What do you recommend the group does - and what is your role in making that happen?","prompt2":"Does knowing about his personal circumstances change your position, and how do you handle that information?","prompt3":"The group submits without him. He later complains to the course coordinator that he was excluded unfairly. You are called in. What do you say?","prompt4":"What does this situation teach you about leadership in a team that is under pressure?","prompt5":"How does this experience change how you will structure group accountability when you are the team leader — and what specific mechanisms will you put in place?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a junior doctor on a busy overnight shift. One of your colleagues - a peer you like and respect - is clearly exhausted and struggling to keep up. Patients are waiting, you are also under pressure, and your colleague has not asked for help. You suspect he is too proud or too anxious to admit he is not coping.","prompt1":"What do you do - and how do you approach it without humiliating him?","prompt2":"What is the line between being a supportive colleague and enabling someone to keep going when they shouldn't?","prompt3":"He insists he is fine and asks you to leave him alone. There is a patient waiting on his list who needs review. What do you do now?","prompt4":"What does a genuinely safe clinical team culture look like - and what does each individual have to do to build it?","prompt5":"What does medicine's culture around admitting struggle cost the profession — and what would you be willing to personally model differently, even if it made you look weak?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a medical student on a ward placement. Your team includes a more senior student who constantly speaks over you in clinical discussions, takes credit for observations you have made, and defers only to the registrar. Other students have noticed but said nothing. The registrar appears oblivious.","prompt1":"How do you handle this?","prompt2":"What stops people from calling out this kind of behaviour in hierarchical environments - and are those reasons justified?","prompt3":"You decide to raise it with the registrar. They respond: 'That's just his personality - he means well.' What do you do now?","prompt4":"Looking ahead, when you are the senior student or registrar, what will you do to prevent this dynamic on your team?","prompt5":"How do you balance developing your own confidence and voice in a hierarchical environment without becoming the person who takes up too much space yourself?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are part of a multidisciplinary team meeting reviewing a patient's discharge plan. The social worker on the team has raised significant concerns about the patient going home to an unsafe environment. The treating consultant is pushing for discharge because of bed pressure. The patient wants to go home. The team is split.","prompt1":"What is your role in this meeting, and how do you contribute constructively?","prompt2":"How do you navigate a situation where the right clinical answer and the system's pressure are pointing in different directions?","prompt3":"The consultant turns to you and asks directly: 'What do you think - does she go home today?' How do you respond?","prompt4":"Who has ultimate responsibility for this decision, and what does shared responsibility in a multidisciplinary team actually mean in practice?","prompt5":"After the meeting ends with a decision you disagreed with, how do you continue to care for this patient wholeheartedly rather than going through the motions — and why does that matter?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. Your team has made a collective error - a delayed diagnosis that you believe was partly due to a handover failure. No lasting harm has occurred. In the debrief, the registrar frames the event in a way that subtly shifts responsibility toward a nurse who was not present to defend herself.","prompt1":"What do you do in the room?","prompt2":"What is your obligation to the nurse who is being implicitly blamed?","prompt3":"Afterward, the registrar privately asks you to 'let it go - it's not going to help anyone to make this bigger than it is.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What does genuine accountability in clinical teams look like - and what makes it so often fail?","prompt5":"What does a team debrief that is actually honest look like — as opposed to one that is performed — and what has to be true about the culture for the former to be possible?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a medical student on placement. A junior nurse approaches you, visibly upset, saying she tried to raise a concern about a medication order with the prescribing resident and was dismissed rudely. She is now unsure whether to escalate. She asks what you think she should do.","prompt1":"What do you say to her - and what is your role here?","prompt2":"Nurses and doctors often operate in overlapping but unequal power structures. How does that shape what she is experiencing and what you can do?","prompt3":"You agree the concern sounds clinically valid. What do you do - do you act, advise, or both?","prompt4":"If you escalate and it turns out the medication order was actually correct, how do you handle that outcome with the nurse and with your team?","prompt5":"What does this situation reveal about the power dynamics between nursing and medical staff — and what will you actively do as a doctor to change those dynamics on your team?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a medical student. Your study group is preparing for exams. Two members have very different learning styles - one wants structured group sessions with assigned roles, the other prefers unstructured discussion. The tension has escalated to the point where both are threatening to leave the group. You are seen as the neutral member.","prompt1":"How do you approach this?","prompt2":"What does this reveal about the assumptions people carry into collaborative work?","prompt3":"Both members independently ask you to 'take their side.' How do you manage the pressure of being asked to choose?","prompt4":"What makes a team more than the sum of its parts - and what breaks that down?","prompt5":"What does this conflict teach you about your own preferences and assumptions around collaboration — and how will you carry that self-knowledge into multidisciplinary teamwork?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. You have been assigned to a team led by a registrar who has a clear favourite - a colleague who gets the interesting cases, positive feedback, and protected teaching time, while the rest of the team are given administrative work and minimal supervision. You are not the favourite. The dynamic is affecting morale.","prompt1":"What, if anything, do you do?","prompt2":"How do you maintain your own learning and motivation when the team environment is working against you?","prompt3":"Two colleagues want to formally complain. A third says 'don't rock the boat, it's only six weeks.' What do you recommend?","prompt4":"When you are a registrar or consultant, what specific behaviours will you commit to that are the opposite of what you are experiencing now?","prompt5":"What does this experience teach you about your own needs for recognition and validation — and how will you manage those needs in a career where fair recognition is not guaranteed?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"A new report shows that life expectancy in remote Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities in Australia is, on average, more than 8 years shorter than for non-Indigenous Australians. You are asked to reflect on this finding.","prompt1":"What are the key drivers of this gap - and which ones do you think are most often overlooked?","prompt2":"What role should doctors and the health system play in addressing this - and where does healthcare end and policy begin?","prompt3":"Someone argues that individual lifestyle choices account for most of the gap and that the health system cannot fix cultural problems. How do you respond?","prompt4":"What would you personally do, as a future doctor, to ensure you are not part of perpetuating this disparity?","prompt5":"A community health worker tells you: 'We do not need more doctors coming here with solutions — we need you to listen first.' What specifically would listening look like in your first month working in that community?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Australia has one of the highest rates of skin cancer in the world, driven largely by UV exposure. Despite decades of public health campaigns, melanoma rates remain high, particularly in men over 50. Reflect on why behaviour change in public health is so difficult.","prompt1":"Why do you think public health campaigns often fail to change entrenched behaviour - using sun exposure as your example?","prompt2":"What approaches beyond awareness campaigns have evidence behind them - and why are they often not adopted?","prompt3":"Should sunscreen be subsidised by the government as a healthcare measure? Walk me through your reasoning.","prompt4":"How does this problem differ across socioeconomic groups in Australia - and what does that mean for how we design solutions?","prompt5":"In your clinic, a tradie in his 50s dismisses your advice about sun protection, saying he has been working outdoors for 30 years and is fine. What do you actually say — not the ideal consultation, the real one?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Mental health presentations have increased significantly in Australian emergency departments over the past decade, particularly among 15-24 year olds. Wait times in EDs for mental health patients are often longer than for physical health presentations.","prompt1":"What do you think are the main drivers of the increase in youth mental health presentations to emergency?","prompt2":"Is the emergency department the right place for most of these presentations? What would a better system look like?","prompt3":"How does socioeconomic disadvantage shape both the risk of mental illness and access to appropriate care?","prompt4":"If you were advising the Victorian government on three specific, fundable actions to reduce preventable youth mental health ED presentations, what would they be?","prompt5":"What would you say to a young person who presents to ED in crisis but leaves after a four-hour wait without being seen — and what does your answer tell you about what the system owes them?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Rates of loneliness and social isolation among older Australians have increased significantly, with research linking isolation to outcomes comparable to smoking 15 cigarettes a day. As a GP, you are seeing more patients over 70 who describe having no one to talk to.","prompt1":"What does this trend tell you about the limits of what healthcare can address alone?","prompt2":"What practical things can a GP do within a standard consultation to identify and address isolation in older patients?","prompt3":"A colleague says this is a social problem, not a medical one, and GPs should not be expected to fill the gaps left by policy failure. How do you respond?","prompt4":"What would a genuinely effective policy response to aged isolation look like — and why does it not currently exist?","prompt5":"An 81-year-old patient tells you this will be his last appointment because he cannot afford transport anymore. You have fifteen minutes. What do you do?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Vaccination rates in some Australian communities have declined, with clusters of vaccine hesitancy contributing to outbreaks of preventable diseases including measles and whooping cough. A parent in your GP clinic tells you she has decided not to vaccinate her toddler.","prompt1":"What are the main reasons behind vaccine hesitancy - and how do you approach a hesitant parent in a consult?","prompt2":"Is there a point at which government should mandate vaccination - for example, for school attendance? What is your view?","prompt3":"A parent tells you they have done their own research and they trust natural immunity more than the MMR vaccine. How do you respond?","prompt4":"What is the GP's responsibility at the population level, not just the individual consult level, when it comes to vaccination uptake in their community?","prompt5":"If vaccination rates in your local area drop to the point where herd immunity is lost and a preventable outbreak occurs, what do you think you will feel — and is that the right feeling to have?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Australia is experiencing a housing affordability crisis, with rising rates of homelessness and housing stress, particularly in Melbourne and Sydney. Research consistently links housing insecurity with worse health outcomes across almost every measure.","prompt1":"How does housing insecurity affect health - and what mechanisms drive that relationship?","prompt2":"What role should the health system play in addressing housing as a health determinant - and where are the limits of that role?","prompt3":"A medical colleague says: 'We're doctors, not social workers - it's not our job to fix housing.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What would 'health-informed housing policy' look like in practice in Australia?","prompt5":"A patient presents with worsening asthma. You know she is living in a mouldy private rental she cannot afford to leave. You treat the asthma. What do you not treat — and what should medicine do about that gap?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Rates of sexually transmitted infections, including gonorrhoea and syphilis, have been rising in Australia over the past decade, with particular increases in regional areas and among certain communities. Public health campaigns have had limited traction.","prompt1":"What are the barriers to effective STI prevention at both the individual and population level?","prompt2":"How should the health system approach STI screening - universal, targeted, or something else?","prompt3":"There is sometimes reluctance to fund STI prevention campaigns because of community discomfort with explicit sexual health messaging. How do you navigate that political reality as a future doctor?","prompt4":"How does stigma function as a barrier to STI testing and treatment - and what can individual clinicians do about it?","prompt5":"How do you have a frank conversation about sexual health with a patient who is clearly uncomfortable — and what do you do if they shut the conversation down entirely?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Extreme heat events are increasing in frequency and severity across Australia. In the summer of 2024, several regional areas recorded temperatures above 45°C for multiple consecutive days. Older adults, outdoor workers, and people without air conditioning face the greatest risk.","prompt1":"What are the direct health consequences of extreme heat — and which populations are most vulnerable and why?","prompt2":"A 78-year-old patient lives alone, has no air conditioning, and refuses to go to a cooling centre because she does not want to leave her cat. It is forecast to be 47 degrees tomorrow. What do you do?","prompt3":"What does the health system need to do differently to prepare for a future where extreme heat events are routine, not exceptional?","prompt4":"A colleague argues that climate advocacy is outside a doctor's professional remit. How do you respond?","prompt5":"How should medical training change to prepare graduates for a healthcare system increasingly shaped by climate-related health events?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A colleague - a registrar you work well with - accidentally prescribes a medication that a patient's chart clearly listed as an allergy. The error is caught by the pharmacist before the dose is administered. No harm occurs. The registrar is mortified and asks you: 'Do I have to report this?' You know your hospital has a mandatory incident reporting policy.","prompt1":"What do you tell them - and what do you do if they decide not to report?","prompt2":"What is the purpose of mandatory incident reporting in hospitals - and does it lose its value if people fear its consequences?","prompt3":"The registrar says: 'It didn't reach the patient - it's a near miss, not an incident. It doesn't really count.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"How do you create an environment where people report near misses without fear - and what has to change at a system level for that to happen?","prompt5":"What would you want your own doctor to do if they made an error in your care — and how does that change how you approach this situation?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a medical student. During a procedure, you accidentally contaminate a sterile field by brushing against equipment without realising it. The scrub nurse sees it but says nothing, and the procedure continues. Afterwards, alone in the corridor, you are replaying it in your head. Nobody else seems to have noticed.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"The nurse saw it happen. Why might she have said nothing - and does that affect your obligation?","prompt3":"You approach the surgeon who performed the procedure. They sigh and say: 'It happens. The patient will be fine.' How do you feel about that response - and does it close the matter?","prompt4":"What does this experience teach you about the psychological weight of making mistakes in medicine - and how do you manage that going forward?","prompt5":"How do you think this moment will stay with you — and what does the way you carry mistakes say about what kind of doctor you are becoming?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A nurse you work alongside tells you, in passing, that last week she accidentally gave a patient the wrong medication - a low-risk mix-up, quickly resolved, no lasting harm. She reported it internally to her team leader but asks you quietly: 'You won't tell anyone else, will you?' You later discover from the patient file that the incident was not formally documented.","prompt1":"What is your obligation here - and does it differ from your obligation to report something you witnessed directly?","prompt2":"How does the nurse's vulnerability in coming to you shape how you respond?","prompt3":"You discover a week later that the same patient had a delayed complication that may or may not be related to the error. Does this change what you do?","prompt4":"What does this scenario reveal about the gap between what hospitals say about reporting culture and what actually happens in practice?","prompt5":"If you had made the same error — and told a student colleague in passing — what would you want them to do? And does your answer change what you actually do here?"},
{"category":"Cultural Competence","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A male patient from a conservative cultural background refuses to be examined by you, insisting on a male doctor. You are female. The male colleague available is a registrar who is currently with a critically unwell patient.","prompt1":"How do you handle this situation right now?","prompt2":"How do you balance respecting cultural preferences with ensuring equitable access to timely care?","prompt3":"A colleague says: 'If he's in an Australian hospital, he has to accept Australian standards - we can't accommodate every cultural preference.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"How do you ensure your team has structures in place for this kind of situation rather than managing it ad hoc each time?","prompt5":"How do you ensure this patient receives the same quality of care as someone without that preference — and what does that require practically, not philosophically?"},
{"category":"Cultural Competence","scenario":"You are a medical student on placement in a rural clinic that serves a large Aboriginal community. An older woman comes in for a chronic disease review. She is quiet, gives brief answers, and makes no eye contact. The GP you are with later tells you this is common and you should not interpret it as disengagement.","prompt1":"What did you observe, and how did it challenge any assumptions you brought into the room?","prompt2":"How does the history of Aboriginal Australians' relationship with medical institutions shape patient behaviour today?","prompt3":"What specific things would you do differently in this consult to build trust with this patient?","prompt4":"What does 'culturally safe practice' actually mean in a clinical setting - and what does it require of you personally?","prompt5":"What would it mean for this community if every doctor who came through their clinic approached it the way you have just described — and how do you carry that standard into every placement, not just the one where it feels most obvious?"},
{"category":"Cultural Competence","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A family from a Vietnamese background has gathered at the bedside of an elderly relative who has received a serious diagnosis. The family asks you not to tell the patient directly - explaining that in their culture, this would cause harm and that the family takes responsibility for this information.","prompt1":"How do you navigate this?","prompt2":"How do Australian medical ethics frameworks around patient autonomy and truth-telling interact with culturally different approaches to disclosure?","prompt3":"The patient, when briefly alone with you, says: 'Am I going to be okay?' What do you do?","prompt4":"Is there a line at which cultural preference conflicts with your duty of care to the patient - and where would you draw it?","prompt5":"After this consultation, how do you document what happened in a way that protects the patient, respects the family, and is honest — and what happens if the next doctor reads the notes and acts differently?"},
{"category":"Cultural Competence","scenario":"You are a GP. A patient who has recently arrived from Sudan presents with her daughter, who is acting as translator. You have concerns that some of your questions about sensitive health topics - including mental health and reproductive health - may not be being accurately translated. The daughter seems uncomfortable.","prompt1":"How do you manage this consultation?","prompt2":"What are the clinical and ethical risks of using family members as interpreters - particularly children?","prompt3":"The patient seems reluctant to use a professional interpreter through the phone service you offer, saying she trusts her daughter. How do you proceed?","prompt4":"What systemic changes would make this kind of encounter safer and more equitable in Australian general practice?","prompt5":"What would equity in this consultation actually look like — and what would it cost the health system to provide it consistently for every patient in a similar situation?"},
{"category":"Cultural Competence","scenario":"You are a medical student. A classmate makes a comment in a study group about a clinical case that involves an assumption about a patient's drug use linked to their ethnicity. It is said casually and most people laugh. You are the only one who appears uncomfortable.","prompt1":"What do you do in that moment?","prompt2":"How do unconscious bias and casual stereotyping in clinical education affect patient care downstream?","prompt3":"The classmate says: 'It was just a joke - statistically it's actually true.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What is your responsibility as a future doctor to actively challenge this kind of thinking in your cohort?","prompt5":"If you stay silent in this moment, what do you implicitly communicate to the classmate who made the comment, to the others who heard it, and to yourself — and are you comfortable with each of those signals?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"A new infectious disease is spreading internationally. It has a high death rate and no vaccine exists. Australia has recorded its first cases. Experts are divided on how serious the threat is. Misinformation is spreading faster than facts.","prompt1":"What should a public health response prioritise in the first weeks — and how do you make decisions when the evidence is still incomplete?","prompt2":"How do you communicate genuine uncertainty to patients and the public without either minimising a real threat or causing unnecessary panic?","prompt3":"A patient is convinced they have the disease after reading about it online. They are clearly very anxious. You do not think they have it. How do you handle this?","prompt4":"Some argue that governments always overreact to new diseases and the response causes more harm than the disease itself. How do you evaluate that argument?","prompt5":"What does this scenario reveal about the relationship between scientific uncertainty, public trust, and the role of doctors as communicators — not just clinicians?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"Overuse of antibiotics is contributing to a global health crisis in which common infections are becoming harder to treat. Australia is one of the higher-prescribing countries in the developed world.","prompt1":"Why do you think antibiotics get overprescribed — and what does that tell you about the pressures doctors face in everyday consultations?","prompt2":"What is a doctor's individual responsibility when their single decision is unlikely to make a difference, but the collective pattern of those decisions causes serious harm?","prompt3":"A patient demands antibiotics for what is clearly a viral infection and says they will go to another doctor if you don't prescribe. What do you do?","prompt4":"What kinds of changes — in healthcare culture, patient expectations, or policy — would actually shift prescribing behaviour at scale?","prompt5":"A patient you decline to prescribe for goes to another GP and gets them immediately. What do you do with that outcome — and what does it tell you about the limits of individual virtue in a collective problem?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"Australia is a signatory to multiple international frameworks on the right to health, yet it operates a two-tiered healthcare system in which private patients access faster care and greater choice than public patients. Reflect on whether this is ethically defensible.","prompt1":"Is a two-tiered health system ethically defensible - what are the strongest arguments on each side?","prompt2":"How does this affect the doctor's role when treating patients across both tiers?","prompt3":"A wealthy patient on your private list says: 'I've worked hard all my life and paid my taxes - I deserve better care.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What would a more equitable Australian health system look like - and what would have to change to get there?","prompt5":"If you are honest, do you intend to practise in both private and public settings — and what does your answer tell you about your actual position on healthcare equity?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"Climate change is increasingly recognised as the greatest long-term threat to global and Australian public health - through extreme heat events, vector-borne disease expansion, food and water insecurity, and displacement. Australian medical schools are beginning to incorporate climate and health into curricula.","prompt1":"How does climate change affect health in Australia specifically - what are the most significant pathways?","prompt2":"What is the role of doctors and the medical profession in responding to climate change - is it professional, political, or both?","prompt3":"A senior colleague says: 'I became a doctor to treat patients, not to be an environmental activist. This has nothing to do with medicine.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What specific things could Australian hospitals and clinicians do to reduce healthcare's own carbon footprint while improving patient care?","prompt5":"A colleague says talking about climate in a medical consultation is inappropriate and politicises the role. A patient with heat-related illness is in front of you. What do you say — to your colleague, and to your patient?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"A medical degree is long, expensive, and demanding. Many people who start do not finish, and many who finish are not happy. Reflect on what has made you certain enough about this path to pursue it.","prompt1":"What has made you certain - and is it certainty, or is it something else?","prompt2":"Describe a moment when you seriously doubted whether medicine was right for you.","prompt3":"If medicine selected out only people who had never had doubts, what kind of doctors would we produce?","prompt4":"If you are offered a place today, what do you do first - and what will you do when it gets hard?","prompt5":"What would it mean to you — practically and emotionally — if you were not offered a place today? And does your answer to that question tell you anything important?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Think of a doctor or healthcare worker who has genuinely shaped how you think about what medicine should be. This is not about admiration — include something they got wrong, or something you would do differently.","prompt1":"Who are they, and what did they teach you?","prompt2":"What did they get wrong - or what would you do differently - and what does that tell you about your own values?","prompt3":"How do you become the doctor you admire, while avoiding the things you would do differently?","prompt4":"What does this person's example tell you about what medicine requires that no curriculum can teach?","prompt5":"If that person were sitting in this room watching your interview, what would they think — and what would they say to you afterwards?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Medicine has very high rates of burnout, depression, and suicide among its practitioners. Many entered the profession with strong intentions and still struggled.","prompt1":"What is your honest answer - not your polished answer?","prompt2":"What specific warning signs in yourself would tell you that you are heading in the wrong direction?","prompt3":"What would you actually do if you recognised those signs - and have you tested whether you would follow through?","prompt4":"What does the culture of medicine need to change to support doctors better - and what part of that change will you commit to?","prompt5":"If you became a doctor who contributed to another colleague's burnout — through your behaviour, your silence, or the culture you allowed — what would that mean to you?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Project yourself twenty years into the future. You have had the medical career you are hoping for. Think concretely about what it looks like — and about a patient who has seen you at your best.","prompt1":"Describe that career - specifically, not vaguely.","prompt2":"What does the patient say about you - and is that version of you achievable?","prompt3":"What is the gap between who you are today and who that doctor is?","prompt4":"What do you start working on tomorrow?","prompt5":"The gap between who you are today and who that doctor is — what is the single most important thing you need to work on, and what has stopped you from starting already?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a medical student on a ward team. A fellow student consistently interrupts the registrar during teaching rounds, leaving no space for others. Two quieter students tell you privately they have stopped trying to contribute. The registrar has not noticed.","prompt1":"What do you do?","prompt2":"How do you raise this with your fellow student without damaging the team dynamic?","prompt3":"He says he is just enthusiastic and you are being oversensitive. How do you hold your position?","prompt4":"What does this tell you about how hierarchies in medicine can silence people — and what will you do differently as a registrar?","prompt5":"If the quieter students never speak up, what responsibility does each team member have to name a dynamic that isn't working?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a junior doctor on a night shift. Your co-resident is clearly overwhelmed — she has missed two reviews, her documentation is incomplete, and you can see she is struggling. She hasn't asked for help. You are also under pressure.","prompt1":"What do you do right now?","prompt2":"How do you offer help without making her feel like she is failing?","prompt3":"She says she is fine and asks you to back off. A patient on her list still needs urgent review. What now?","prompt4":"What is the difference between respecting a colleague's autonomy and enabling a situation that could harm a patient?","prompt5":"After the shift, how do you raise what happened without it feeling like a formal report?"},
{"category":"Teamwork","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. Your team's consultant clearly has a favourite registrar — who receives interesting cases, protected teaching time, and public praise, while others receive administrative work and minimal feedback. You are not the favourite.","prompt1":"What do you do to protect your own learning in this environment?","prompt2":"How do you raise this with the consultant — or do you?","prompt3":"Two colleagues want to formally complain. One says it is only six weeks, do not rock the boat. What do you recommend?","prompt4":"When you are a consultant yourself, what will you do differently?","prompt5":"What does this experience teach you about the difference between a good clinician and a good team leader?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Type 2 diabetes is one of the fastest growing chronic diseases in Australia, with Aboriginal, Torres Strait Islander, and Pacific Islander communities, and people in lower socioeconomic areas disproportionately affected.","prompt1":"How would you think about preventing type 2 diabetes at a population level — and what would you need to understand before deciding where to focus?","prompt2":"How do the social determinants of health shape diabetes risk — and what does that mean for a strategy focused only on individual behaviour change?","prompt3":"A colleague argues that diabetes prevention is a government problem, not a doctor's job. How do you respond?","prompt4":"What would a culturally safe, community-led diabetes prevention program look like in a remote Indigenous community?","prompt5":"If you had to choose one lever — policy, healthcare system, or community — to reduce diabetes incidence in the next decade, what would it be and why?"},
{"category":"Public Health","scenario":"Food insecurity is a growing issue in Australia, with over one million households estimated to be food insecure. Children in these households have worse educational outcomes, higher rates of developmental delay, and poorer lifelong health.","prompt1":"How does food insecurity affect child health and development?","prompt2":"What are the most effective policy levers for reducing childhood food insecurity in Australia?","prompt3":"Should GPs routinely screen for food insecurity — what are the arguments for and against?","prompt4":"What is your role when a parent tells you in a consultation they are skipping meals so their children can eat?","prompt5":"How does food insecurity intersect with other social determinants to compound disadvantage — and what does that mean for how healthcare responds?"},
{"category":"Rural Health","scenario":"You are a medical student considering a rural career. Most graduates say they are open to rural practice and then end up in cities. Reflect honestly on why that happens — and what would actually change it.","prompt1":"Why do most graduates end up in metropolitan areas despite stated interest in rural practice?","prompt2":"What would genuinely change the distribution of doctors into rural and remote areas?","prompt3":"What specifically draws you to rural medicine — and what concerns you about it?","prompt4":"A rural GP says: 'I have heard this from students every year for 20 years. What makes you actually different?' How do you respond?","prompt5":"What do rural communities actually need from doctors — and is that different from what urban communities need?"},
{"category":"Rural Health","scenario":"You are a junior doctor considering a rural generalist pathway. Reflect on the unique clinical demands and ethical challenges of rural practice — not as abstractions, but as things you have thought seriously about.","prompt1":"What clinical skills and responsibilities distinguish rural generalism from metropolitan practice?","prompt2":"What are the ethical challenges specific to being the only doctor — or one of very few — in a community?","prompt3":"A patient you know socially presents with a sensitive mental health issue. How do you navigate being both doctor and community member?","prompt4":"Rural areas have significantly higher rates of suicide, particularly in farming communities. How should this shape a rural GP's practice?","prompt5":"What does cultural safety mean in a rural context — and how does it differ from cultural safety in a metropolitan Indigenous health setting?"},
{"category":"Rural Health","scenario":"A rural town of 800 people has lost its only GP. The nearest emergency department is 90 minutes away. You are a medical student asked to reflect on this scenario.","prompt1":"What are the immediate health consequences of a town losing its only GP?","prompt2":"What systemic factors led to this situation — and who is responsible for addressing it?","prompt3":"A community member says: 'The government keeps promising things but nothing changes. What makes you think you would be any different?' How do you respond?","prompt4":"What strategies have evidence behind them for attracting and retaining GPs in very remote areas?","prompt5":"If you were designing a medical training pathway from scratch to produce more rural doctors, what would it look like — and when would rural exposure begin?"},
{"category":"Rural Health","scenario":"You are a junior doctor who has just completed your first solo overnight shift in a rural hospital. You had to make several decisions without a senior doctor available. One patient deteriorated and needed urgent transfer. You are exhausted and not sure whether you made the right calls.","prompt1":"What is going through your mind the morning after that shift — and how do you sit with uncertainty about your own decisions?","prompt2":"What does it feel like to bear responsibility before you feel fully ready — and how do you function in that gap?","prompt3":"Your supervisor reviews the night and tells you that you were too cautious on one decision, and too bold on another. How do you receive that feedback?","prompt4":"What is the emotional weight of being responsible for people in an under-resourced setting — and how do you sustain yourself long-term without becoming either reckless or paralysed?","prompt5":"How should medical training prepare graduates for the reality that they will face decisions alone, under pressure, before they feel ready — and what is currently missing from that preparation?"},
{"category":"Rural Health","scenario":"Rural Australians have significantly higher rates of chronic disease, injury, and preventable death than metropolitan Australians. Reflect on why this gap exists and what can realistically be done about it.","prompt1":"What are the key drivers of worse health outcomes in rural Australia?","prompt2":"How much of this gap is due to healthcare access, and how much is due to the social determinants of health?","prompt3":"A policy maker argues that telehealth has effectively closed the access gap. How do you evaluate that claim?","prompt4":"How does rurality intersect with Indigenous status, poverty, and occupation in ways that compound health risk?","prompt5":"If you had to choose one investment to improve rural health outcomes over the next decade, what would it be and why?"},
{"category":"Rural Health","scenario":"You are a medical student on a rural placement. Your supervisor, the only GP in town, tells you he has not had a holiday in 14 months and has been covering the ED overnight twice a week. He seems fine but is short-tempered with a patient today.","prompt1":"What do you observe — and what, if anything, do you say to your supervisor?","prompt2":"What does this situation reveal about the structural conditions rural GPs work in?","prompt3":"Your supervisor says: 'This is just the job. If you cannot handle it, rural medicine is not for you.' How do you process that?","prompt4":"What would genuine systemic support for rural GPs look like — and why does it not exist in its current form?","prompt5":"If you do pursue rural practice, what will you do proactively to sustain yourself in a way your supervisor has not?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"The life expectancy gap between Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians and non-Indigenous Australians has persisted despite decades of policy attention. Reflect on why this is the case.","prompt1":"What are the root causes of this persistent gap?","prompt2":"Why do you think targeted health policies have so often fallen short — and what does that pattern suggest about what genuine progress would require?","prompt3":"A colleague argues that individual lifestyle choices account for most of the gap and the health system cannot fix cultural problems. How do you respond?","prompt4":"What does genuine community self-determination in health look like — and how is it different from what has been attempted so far?","prompt5":"What would you personally do, as a future doctor, to ensure you are not part of perpetuating this disparity?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"You are a medical student on placement in a clinic serving a predominantly Aboriginal community. An older woman comes for a chronic disease review. She gives brief answers, makes no eye contact, and seems disengaged.","prompt1":"What did you observe — and what assumptions did you bring into the room?","prompt2":"How does the history of Aboriginal Australians' relationship with healthcare institutions shape patient behaviour today?","prompt3":"What would you do differently in this consultation to build trust?","prompt4":"What does culturally safe practice actually mean in a clinical setting — and what does it require of you personally?","prompt5":"Your supervisor says 'you will get used to it.' What concerns you about that framing — and what would a better response look like?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"Closing the Gap is Australia's national framework for addressing Indigenous health and social inequalities. Reflect on what it has achieved, where it has fallen short, and what genuine progress would require.","prompt1":"What is your understanding of what Closing the Gap is trying to achieve — and what have you observed or read about its track record?","prompt2":"What has it achieved, and where has it fallen short?","prompt3":"Indigenous leaders criticised earlier versions for being designed without genuine community involvement. What does co-design in health policy actually require?","prompt4":"How does the social determinants framework apply to Indigenous health in ways that purely biomedical approaches do not capture?","prompt5":"If you were a junior doctor working in a remote Indigenous community, what would you prioritise in your practice to contribute to closing the gap from the clinical level up?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. An Aboriginal patient in his 40s has been admitted with a serious but manageable condition. He is reluctant to accept the treatment plan and repeatedly asks when he can go home. His family is in the carpark and has not been allowed on the ward due to visiting restrictions.","prompt1":"How do you approach this consultation?","prompt2":"What might explain his reluctance — and how does the history of Aboriginal people in institutional settings shape this moment?","prompt3":"You want to involve his family but ward policy limits visitors. How do you navigate this?","prompt4":"He discharges himself against medical advice. What is your responsibility at this point?","prompt5":"What would this ward need to change structurally to provide genuinely culturally safe care to Aboriginal patients?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A colleague makes an offhand comment in the staff room linking a patient's non-compliance with their cultural background. It is said without malice, as if it is simply obvious. Two nurses laugh. You are the most junior person in the room.","prompt1":"What do you do in that moment — and what makes it harder than it sounds?","prompt2":"Your colleague later says: \"I wasn't being racist, I was being realistic — it's a pattern I've seen.\" How do you respond?","prompt3":"How does this kind of assumption — even when not malicious — affect the care this patient receives from that point forward?","prompt4":"What is your responsibility to this patient, who is not in the room and does not know this conversation happened?","prompt5":"If you say nothing, what do you communicate to your colleague, to the nurses, and to yourself — and are you willing to carry that?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"You are a GP. A young Aboriginal woman mentions she avoids the hospital nearby because of how they treated her aunt. She does not elaborate. You know the hospital has documented complaints about care of Aboriginal patients.","prompt1":"How do you respond to this in the consultation?","prompt2":"What does her comment tell you about the lived experience of Aboriginal patients navigating the health system?","prompt3":"Should you do anything about the hospital she mentioned — and if so, what?","prompt4":"How do you build enough trust in this consultation that she feels safe to return?","prompt5":"What would systemic accountability for culturally unsafe care actually look like — and who should be responsible for it?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"The health of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities today has been shaped by historical events and ongoing structural conditions. Reflect on what that means for how you should practise.","prompt1":"What do you understand about the historical and structural factors that have shaped Indigenous health outcomes in Australia?","prompt2":"How do the effects of dispossession, removal policies, and intergenerational disadvantage show up in health outcomes and healthcare interactions today?","prompt3":"A colleague says: 'That is history — we need to focus on what we can do clinically now.' How do you respond?","prompt4":"How should medical training prepare graduates to practise in communities with this history — and what is currently missing from curricula?","prompt5":"What specific commitments would you make in your own practice to ensure history actively informs how you see and treat Indigenous patients?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"Many Western medicine frameworks do not align with Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander understandings of health and wellbeing, which are holistic and include connection to Country, community, and spirit. Reflect on what this means for clinical practice.","prompt1":"What do you understand about how Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities conceptualise health — and how does it differ from the biomedical model?","prompt2":"How should this difference shape how a doctor conducts a consultation with an Aboriginal patient?","prompt3":"A senior clinician says patient-centred care already covers this and no special framework is needed. How do you respond?","prompt4":"How do you learn about a community's health beliefs and values without making assumptions or stereotyping?","prompt5":"What does it mean to be a culturally safe practitioner in practice — not as a concept, but as a set of daily behaviours?"},
{"category":"Indigenous Health","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. Your team is discussing a young Aboriginal man who has been repeatedly presenting to emergency with alcohol-related presentations. A colleague says under their breath: 'He will be back again next week.' No one responds.","prompt1":"What is happening in that room — and what do you do?","prompt2":"What does that comment reflect about attitudes that persist in healthcare — and what are its consequences for this patient's care?","prompt3":"You later see this patient in the ED. How does this moment in the corridor change how you approach the consultation?","prompt4":"How do you raise systemic attitudes like this with your team without creating a defensive backlash?","prompt5":"What does this situation reveal about the relationship between institutional racism and individual health outcomes?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor during a period of extreme resource pressure. Your hospital has one ICU bed remaining. Two patients need it urgently: a 34-year-old mother of three with a treatable condition and a good prognosis, and a 67-year-old man with a more complex situation and a less certain outcome. Both will likely die without the bed. You are the most senior person available right now.","prompt1":"How do you think about this decision — and what framework, if any, guides you?","prompt2":"The 34-year-old's husband is in the corridor and knows there is one bed left. The 67-year-old has no family present. Does that change anything — and why?","prompt3":"You make the call. Whichever patient does not get the bed dies. How do you carry that decision — tonight, and in ten years?","prompt4":"This decision should not fall on a single junior doctor in a corridor. What does that tell you about how healthcare systems should be designed?","prompt5":"If you were the patient who did not get the bed, and you found out the reasoning that led to that decision, what would you want to have been considered — and does your answer change how you think about the decision you just made?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"A patient you have been looking after for three weeks — someone you have genuinely come to like — is dying. The medicine has done what it can. She knows it. You walk into her room not to do anything clinical, just because you were passing and the door was open. She looks up and says: \"I'm scared.\" You have five minutes.","prompt1":"What do you say — not what you should say, what you actually say?","prompt2":"There is nothing clinical you can offer. What does it feel like to be in a room where medicine has reached its limit — and what does that ask of you as a person rather than a doctor?","prompt3":"Later, a colleague says: \"You shouldn't get attached — it makes you less effective.\" How do you respond?","prompt4":"How do you walk out of that room and see the next patient?","prompt5":"What do you think that patient needed in those five minutes — and did you give it to her?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a medical student on placement. During a ward round, you notice the consultant always addresses male students first, asks them more complex questions, and visibly engages more with their answers. The female students in your group have noticed too. No one has said anything. The consultant is not hostile — he appears completely unaware of the pattern.","prompt1":"You have noticed this. You are not the person most affected by it. What is your responsibility?","prompt2":"One of the female students tells you privately she has stopped trying to answer because she has given up expecting to be called on. What do you do with that?","prompt3":"You raise it with the consultant directly. He becomes defensive and says he treats everyone equally. How do you proceed?","prompt4":"If you say nothing and the pattern continues for the rest of the term, what are you implicitly communicating — to him, to your female colleagues, and to yourself?","prompt5":"How does this experience shape what you commit to doing when you are the consultant — and how specific are you willing to be about that commitment?"},
{"category":"Motivation","scenario":"Most conversations about medicine focus on its demands — the pressure, the sacrifice, the darkness. But medicine is also full of extraordinary moments: things you cannot fully explain, connections you did not expect, cases that change how you see the world. Think about something in or around healthcare that has genuinely amazed you — not inspired you to help, but actually stopped you.","prompt1":"What was it — and what was it about that specific thing that got to you?","prompt2":"That kind of wonder tends to get trained out of doctors over time. What do you think causes that — and how do you intend to protect it in yourself?","prompt3":"Is there a tension between being rigorous and scientific and being genuinely moved by what you see? How do you hold both?","prompt4":"The best doctors, by most accounts, maintain curiosity throughout their careers. What is the difference between someone who does and someone who doesn't — and which one are you more likely to become?","prompt5":"If the wonder disappears — if medicine becomes just a series of problems to solve — what would that tell you about what has happened to you, and what would you do about it?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. A 58-year-old man with a completely treatable cancer has decided, after careful consideration, to refuse all treatment. He is not depressed. He has capacity. He has thought about this for months. He tells you clearly: he has seen what treatment does to people, he has had a good life, and he would rather die on his own terms than spend his remaining time being sick from chemotherapy. His wife is devastated and has asked you to change his mind.","prompt1":"What is your role here — and is it different from what his wife wants it to be?","prompt2":"You personally believe he is making the wrong decision. Does that change what you do?","prompt3":"His wife says: \"He's not thinking straight — he's just scared of hospitals.\" You have assessed him and believe he has full capacity. How do you respond to her?","prompt4":"He dies six months later, without treatment, at home. What do you think about when you hear the news?","prompt5":"What does respecting autonomy actually cost a doctor — emotionally, not professionally — and how do you sustain that commitment over a career of similar decisions?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"There is a version of yourself that you perform — for interviews, for supervisors, for patients, for this room right now. And there is the version that exists when no one important is watching: when you are tired, when it does not matter, when there are no consequences. Think honestly about the gap between those two versions.","prompt1":"What does the unobserved version of you look like — and how different is it from what you present?","prompt2":"Medicine is full of moments where no one is watching: the note you write at midnight, the phone call you return or don't, the patient you spend five minutes with or fifteen. Which version of you shows up in those moments?","prompt3":"Is the gap between your public and private self something to be ashamed of, or is it just human — and how do you know the difference?","prompt4":"What would have to be true about your character for the observed and unobserved versions to be the same person?","prompt5":"If a colleague you trusted had watched everything you did last week — not the highlights, everything — would you be comfortable with what they saw?"},
{"category":"Personal","scenario":"You are a volunteer at a soup kitchen. You get to know a man named Martin — intelligent, funny, once a teacher. Over several months you watch him deteriorate: thinner, more erratic, eventually absent for weeks at a time. When he comes back he is clearly in a very bad way. You are not his doctor. You are not his family. You have no formal role. You cannot fix what is happening to him.","prompt1":"What do you do with what you are watching — and what does it cost you to keep showing up?","prompt2":"There is a difference between helping and witnessing. What does it mean to witness someone's suffering when you cannot change it?","prompt3":"Martin tells you one evening he does not want help. He wants to be treated normally — just talked to. What does that ask of you?","prompt4":"How does this experience change, if at all, how you see people you will encounter in medicine who are in Martin's situation?","prompt5":"Doctors are trained to act, to diagnose, to treat. What happens when the most important thing is simply to be present — and how do you get good at that?"},
{"category":"Conflict Resolution","scenario":"You are a final-year medical student. A patient you have spent forty minutes assessing tells you she has been seen by two other doctors this week and both told her there was nothing seriously wrong. After talking with her carefully, you are genuinely concerned — something does not add up. You raise it with your supervising registrar, who glances at the notes and says: \"Two experienced doctors have already seen her. I think you're overthinking it.\"","prompt1":"What do you do — and how confident do you need to be before you push back against a registrar dismissing your concern?","prompt2":"You are a student. She has been seen by two doctors. What is the reasonable threshold for insisting something has been missed?","prompt3":"The registrar says: \"This is a pattern with new students — you catastrophise because you don't have the experience to calibrate risk yet.\" Is that a fair point — and how do you hold it alongside your genuine concern?","prompt4":"You let it go. Three days later the patient is readmitted in a serious condition. How do you process that — and what do you do with it?","prompt5":"What does this situation teach you about when to trust your instincts and when to trust hierarchy — and is there a principle that guides that, or is it always a judgement call?"},
{"category":"Ethics","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. An elderly patient you have been looking after for three weeks — someone who has been difficult, demanding, and occasionally unkind — surprises you on the day of his discharge. He is tearful. He thanks you in a way that is clearly genuine, and then hands you an envelope. Inside is $300 cash and a note that says: \"You're the first person in here who actually treated me like a person.\"","prompt1":"What do you do in that moment — right there, with the envelope in your hand?","prompt2":"You know you are supposed to decline. But the money is real, your rent is due, and his gratitude is genuine. Walk through your actual internal reasoning.","prompt3":"He becomes upset when you try to decline. \"You people take everything else — you can't take this one thing?\" How do you respond?","prompt4":"What is the rule about gifts from patients actually protecting — the patient, the doctor, the profession, or something else?","prompt5":"What does accepting or declining this gift communicate to him about what his care meant — and is that consideration part of your decision?"},
{"category":"Policy","scenario":"You are a junior doctor. You have now worked in three different hospitals. In every one of them, you have observed the same pattern: junior doctors are routinely rostered beyond safe working hours, documentation is systematically incomplete because there is no time to do it properly, and near-misses go unreported because the culture treats reporting as disloyalty. No individual is the villain. The system produces these outcomes.","prompt1":"What do you do with this observation — as a junior doctor, right now, with very little power?","prompt2":"Reporting individual incidents feels pointless when the incidents are structural. What is the right level to intervene at — and who has the power to do it?","prompt3":"A senior colleague says: \"Every generation of junior doctors thinks the system is broken. It has always been this way and it functions. You will get used to it.\" How do you respond?","prompt4":"What is the cost of getting used to it — to you, to your colleagues, and to patients?","prompt5":"What would it actually take to change a culture like this — and are you willing to pay what that requires, knowing that the people who benefit from the change may never know your name?"}];



